berg\n |WrittenBy       = Chris Connolly, Jenny Connell Davis, Jeremy Lubman and Bryan Wizemann\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|06|14}}\n  |ShortSummary    = Overconsumption has led us to a point where the human race will either have to engineer our way around our supply and demand problems, or we will have to look to other planets to inhabit. This episode asks if it is possible that alien civilizations have already solved similar problems.\n |LineColor       = #FFCC00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = Beyond The Cosmos\n |DirectedBy      = Mark Elijah Rosenberg\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Andr\u00e9 Bormanis|t=Andr\u00e9 Bormanis and Paul Solet}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|06|21}}\n  |ShortSummary    = We have always been a species that is compelled to explore. This spirit has led us to new shores and recently to the planets of our solar system. As the number of places remaining to be explored on Earth vanishes, this episode asks how we might have to adapt ourselves to explore the further reaches of space.\n |LineColor       = #FFCC00\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Geographic TV}}\n\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about science]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about space]]\n[[Category:Documentary television series about technology]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Science education television series]]\n[[Category:Science fiction television films]]\n", "name_user": "Gildir", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Year_Million"}
{"title_page": "Peter Vaughan (bishop)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|RRevd}}\n| name             = Peter Vaughan\n| honorific-suffix = [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA(Cantab) MA(Oxon)]]\n| title            = [[Bishop of Ramsbury]]\n| diocese          = [[Diocese of Salisbury]]\n| term             = 1989\u20131998\n| predecessor      = [[John Neale (bishop)|John Neale]]\n| successor        = [[Peter Hullah]]\n| other_post       = [[Assistant bishop|Honorary assistant bishop]] in [[Diocese of Gloucester|Gloucester]] and in [[Diocese of Bristol|Bristol]] (2002\u20132011); in [[Diocese of Bradford|Bradford]] (1998\u20132001)<br />[[Archdeacon of Westmorland and Furness]] (1983\u20131989)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 1957 (deacon); 1958 (priest)\n| consecration     = 1989\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1930|11|27|df=y}}\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| parents          = Dr Victor & Dorothy\n| spouse           = Elisabeth Parker (m. 1961)\n| children         = 1 son; 2 daughters\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n'''Peter St George Vaughan''' (born 27 November 1930)<ref>\u2018VAUGHAN, Rt Rev. Peter St George\u2019, Who's Who 2012, A & C Black, 2012; online edition, Oxford University Press, December 2011 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U41022], accessed 10 July 2012</ref> was the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Ramsbury]] from 1989 to 1998.<ref>''Debrett's People of Today 1992'' (London, [[Debrett's]]) {{ISBN|1-870520-09-2}})</ref>\n\nVaughan was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] before beginning his ordained ministry as a [[curate]] at Birmingham Parish Church, followed by an appointment as a chaplain to The Oxford Pastorate based at St Aldate's Church, Oxford. He was then [[Vicar]] of [[Christ Church Galle Face Colombo Sri Lanka] before becoming the [[Precentor]] of [[Holy Trinity Cathedral, Auckland]] and then [[Dean (religion)|Principal]] of the [[Church Mission Society]] [[college]] at [[Selly Oak]] and  then (his final appointment before ordination to the [[episcopate]]) [[Archdeacon of Westmorland and Furness]].<ref>''[[Crockford's clerical directory]] 1995'' (Lambeth, Church House {{ISBN|0-7151-8088-6}})</ref> In retirement he continues as an [[assistant bishop]] in the [[Diocese of Gloucester]].<ref>[http://www.bnc.ox.ac.uk/downloads/brazen_notes/thebrazennose2004.pdf Details of service]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Neale (bishop)|John Neale]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Ramsbury]]|years=1989\u20131998}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Peter Hullah]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Ramsbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaughan, Peter St George}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Westmorland and Furness]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Ramsbury]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{ChurchofEngland-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|RRevd}}\n| name             = Peter Vaughan\n| honorific-suffix = [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA(Cantab) MA(Oxon)]]\n| title            = [[Bishop of Ramsbury]]\n| diocese          = [[Diocese of Salisbury]]\n| term             = 1989\u20131998\n| predecessor      = [[John Neale (bishop)|John Neale]]\n| successor        = [[Peter Hullah]]\n| other_post       = [[Assistant bishop|Honorary assistant bishop]] in [[Diocese of Gloucester|Gloucester]] and in [[Diocese of Bristol|Bristol]] (2002\u20132011); in [[Diocese of Bradford|Bradford]] (1998\u20132001)<br />[[Archdeacon of Westmorland and Furness]] (1983\u20131989)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 1957 (deacon); 1958 (priest)\n| consecration     = 1989\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1930|11|27|df=y}}\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| parents          = Dr Victor & Dorothy\n| spouse           = Elisabeth Parker (m. 1961)\n| children         = 1 son; 2 daughters\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n'''Peter St George Vaughan''' (born 27 November 1930)<ref>\u2018VAUGHAN, Rt Rev. Peter St George\u2019, Who's Who 2012, A & C Black, 2012; online edition, Oxford University Press, December 2011 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U41022], accessed 10 July 2012</ref> was the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Ramsbury]] from 1989 to 1998.<ref>''Debrett's People of Today 1992'' (London, [[Debrett's]]) {{ISBN|1-870520-09-2}})</ref>\n\nVaughan was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] before beginning his ordained ministry as a [[curate]] at Birmingham Parish Church, followed by an appointment as a chaplain to The Oxford Pastorate based at St Aldate's Church, Oxford. He was then [[Vicar]] of [[Galle Face]] before becoming the [[Precentor]] of [[Holy Trinity Cathedral, Auckland]] and then [[Dean (religion)|Principal]] of the [[Church Mission Society]] [[college]] at [[Selly Oak]] and  then (his final appointment before ordination to the [[episcopate]]) [[Archdeacon of Westmorland and Furness]].<ref>''[[Crockford's clerical directory]] 1995'' (Lambeth, Church House {{ISBN|0-7151-8088-6}})</ref> In retirement he continues as an [[assistant bishop]] in the [[Diocese of Gloucester]].<ref>[http://www.bnc.ox.ac.uk/downloads/brazen_notes/thebrazennose2004.pdf Details of service]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Neale (bishop)|John Neale]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Ramsbury]]|years=1989\u20131998}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Peter Hullah]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Ramsbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaughan, Peter St George}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Westmorland and Furness]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Ramsbury]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{ChurchofEngland-bishop-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nilkantha Peiris", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Vaughan_(bishop)"}
{"title_page": "Tim Gettinger", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Tim Gettinger\n| image = Hartford Wolf Pack - Tim Gettinger.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Tim Gettinger on December 14, 2019\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|04|14}}\n| birth_place = [[North Olmsted, Ohio]], U.S.\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lb = 216\n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)|Forward]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[New York Rangers]]\n| prospect_team = [[Hartford Wolf Pack]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = \n| ntl_team = \n| draft = 141st overall\n| draft_year = 2016\n| draft_team = [[New York Rangers]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end =\n}}\n'''Timothy Gettinger''' (born April 14, 1998) is an [[Americans|American]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Forward (ice hockey)|forward]] for the [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) as a prospect to the [[New York Rangers]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). He was selected by the Rangers in the fifth round, 141st overall, in the [[2016 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Herman |first=Adam |url=https://www.blueshirtbanter.com/2016/6/25/12030198/nhl-draft-2016-rangers-select-left-wing-tim-gettinger-141st-overall |title=NHL Draft 2016: Rangers Select Left Wing Timothy Gettinger 141st Overall |publisher=blueshirtbanter.com |date=June 25, 2016 |accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> He had served as [[Captain (ice hockey)|captain]] for the [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]] (OHL).\n\n==Playing career==\nGettinger first played midget hockey in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] with the Barons. In his first season with the [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]] (OHL) in the [[2014\u201315 OHL season|2014\u201315 season]], Gettinger scored 10 goals. In the second season with the Greyhounds, his totals improved to 17 goals and 39 points in 60 games for the [[2015\u201316 OHL season|2015\u201316 season]].\n\nOn June 24, 2016, Gettinger was selected 141st overall by the [[New York Rangers]] during the [[2016 NHL Entry Draft]]. Gettinger entered the draft as the 65th ranked prospect.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Kerr |url=http://lastwordonsports.com/2016/06/04/tim-gettinger-scouting-report-2016-nhl-draft-65/ |title=Tim Gettinger Scouting Report: 2016 NHL Draft #65 |publisher=lastwordonsports.com |date=June 4, 2016| accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2017, the Rangers signed Gettinger to a three-year, entry-level contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rangers Agree to Terms With Forward Tim Gettinger |url=https://www.nhl.com/rangers/news/rangers-agree-to-terms-with-forward-tim-gettinger/c-287765306 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, 2017, Gettinger was named [[Captain (ice hockey)|captain]] of the Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruicci |first1=Peter |title=Greyhounds name Gettinger captain |url=http://www.saultstar.com/2017/10/12/greyhounds-name-gettinger-captain |website=Sault Star |accessdate=October 25, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026110719/http://www.saultstar.com/2017/10/12/greyhounds-name-gettinger-captain |archivedate=October 26, 2017 |date=October 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGettinger began the 2018\u201319 season with the [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL). He was recalled by the Rangers due to an injury to forward [[Mats Zuccarello]] on November 23, 2018, and played his first NHL game the next day with the Rangers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rangers Recall Tim Gettinger From Hartford |url=https://www.nhl.com/rangers/news/rangers-recall-tim-gettinger-from-hartford/c-302228142 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=November 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Brooks |first1=Larry |title=Rangers playing it \u2018cautious\u2019 with Mats Zuccarello |url=https://nypost.com/2018/11/24/rangers-playing-it-cautious-with-mats-zuccarello/ |website=New York Post |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=November 24, 2018}}</ref> He was returned to Harford after playing one game,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rangers' Tim Gettinger sent back down to Hartford after Saturday's game |url=https://www.sny.tv/rangers/news/rangers-tim-gettinger-sent-back-down-to-hartford-after-saturdays-game/301069904 |website=SNY |accessdate=November 25, 2018 |date=November 24, 2018}}</ref> only to be recalled the next day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rangers Recall Tim Gettinger From Hartford |url=https://www.nhl.com/rangers/news/rangers-recall-tim-gettinger-from-hartford/c-302295932 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=November 29, 2018 |date=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career Statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]] \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]] \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| [[2014\u201315 OHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| 54\n| 10\n| 15\n| 25\n| 13\n| 6\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2015\u201316 OHL season|2015\u201316]]\n| Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds\n| OHL\n| 60\n| 17\n| 22\n| 39\n| 32\n| 12\n| 1\n| 3\n| 4\n| 0\n|- \n| [[2016\u201317 OHL season|2016\u201317]]\n| Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds\n| OHL\n| 62\n| 31\n| 23\n| 54\n| 27\n| 11\n| 4\n| 3\n| 7\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2017\u201318 OHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds\n| OHL\n| 63\n| 33\n| 36\n| 69\n| 53\n| 24\n| 