{"title_page": "Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez", "text_new": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = Tadeo Ribera Bruckner (1990-?), H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal (?-present)\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the center-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nJeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez was born in the small Amazonian town of [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]] in the [[Department of Beni]], Bolivia, on 13 August 1967. She was the youngest of seven children born to two teachers.<ref name=biografias>{{cite web|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/bolivien/10697.pdf|language=es|title=BIOGRAF\u00cdAS Historias de Vida en la Asamblea Legislativa Plurinacional|year=2013|page=416\u2013418}}</ref> Her background has been described as poor [[mestiza]] and lower-middle-class.<ref name=\"\u201ceconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=CIDOB>{{cite web|url=https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |website=www.cidob.org|language=es|date=13 December 2019}}</ref> During this time, San Joaqu\u00edn lacked proper roads, was dependent on diesel generators for power and had a water supply that was rationed. Recalling her childhood, she says \"We grew up with many limitations, with many needs but nevertheless I had a beautiful childhood, very free.\" <ref name=biografias></ref>\n\nShe attended the local school, a girls school that her mother would later become director of. At age seventeen, she achieved her baccalaureate and left San Joaqu\u00edn to pursue an education in La Paz, first at the Bolivian Institute and then at the Abraham Lincoln Institute. At this time, she studied to become a secretary.<ref name=biografias></ref> She continued to [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] where she took further studies as a secretary, including computing and some English. <ref name=biografias></ref> After getting married at aged 23, she moved to [[Trinidad, Bolivia]], where she enrolled at the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n and obtained a graduate degree in law and legal sciences.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvisi\u00f3n.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she spoke out against the approval of a finance bill by the Morales' government for the construction of the Villa Tunari-San Ignacio de Moxos highway. She claimed that it was not approved with due consideration for the native peoples and institutions of the region saying that \"indigenous people's right was violated\", a sentiment echoed by leader of the natives of the Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park Indigenous Territory (TIPNIS), Adolfo Moye who said it was enacted \"without considering the serious impact on the ecosystem and natural reserves of the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20110511/senadora-cuestiona-financiamiento-carretera-cochabamba-beni|title=Senator questions financing of Cochabamba-Beni highway|language=es|date=11 May 2011|website=www.losttiempos.com|}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, A\u00f1ez and fellow party legislator Adri\u00e1n Oliva presented a report to the Human Rights Commission of the Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay in an effort to publicise human rights violations in Bolivia. According to the UN refugee office, UNHCR, there were around 600 Bolivian exiles or refugees, a hundred political prisoners and at least 15 cases of torture at this time. The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights stated that there was a \"crisis in the administration of justice\" in Bolivia. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120523/presentan-informe-uruguay|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=23 May 2012|language=es|title=Report presented in Uruguay}}</ref> Also in 2012, A\u00f1ez was selected as a Bolivian representative to the Amazonian Parliament. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120316/senado-designo-representantes-parlamentos-internacionales|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=16 March 2012|language=es|title=Senate designates representatives to international parliaments.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, there were a series of nationwide strikes and protests against the MAS government concerning the reduction of seats in the Chamber of Deputies for the areas of [[Department of Beni|Beni]], [[Potos\u00ed department|Potos\u00ed]] and [[Department of Chuquisaca|Chuquisaca]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/2/beni-potosi-inician-paro-contra-escanos-2058.html|date=2 October 2013}}</ref>As Senator of Beni, Jeanine A\u00f1ez joined picket lines and was among six legistlators and a dozen indigenous representatives of [[CONAMAQ]] that went on hunger strike in protest to the legistlation being passed by the MAS majority in both chambers. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/conflicto-escanos-agrava-tres-piquetes-huelguistas-2255.html|title=Conflict over seats worsens, there are three pickets of strikers|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/opositores-bolivianos-inician-huelga-hambre-contra-reduccion-escanos-2289.html|title=Bolivian opposition members start hunger strike against reduction of seats|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, \u00c1\u00f1ez made complaints about the lack of financial transparency from the government. Requests for reports as part of opposition legislators ability to audit the activities of the state were delayed and in 499 out of 1979 cases for the 2013-14 period received no response. The authorities, according to the regulations of the Chamber of Deputies, were permitted 10 business days to respond to a request for a report, and in the Senate, 15 days. If the request for a written report is not answered, an injunction can be issued to give a time limit of 48 hours. \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases, these injunctions were ignored and there was a \"denial of information\". Many of the projects had multi-million budgets with several interested parties for whom access is even more restricted.  \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases which do receive replies \"they are responses without response\". Responses included two sheets of photocopies, material unrelated to the request or boxes full of documents which do \"not intend to clarify the doubts, but to hinder the work of the legislators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2014/2/9/denuncian-trabas-acceso-informacion-para-fiscalizar-13544.html|title=They denounce obstacles in access to information for auditing|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> In 2019-2020, many of these cases are under investigation. <ref name=corruption>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/22/bolivia-se-suman-denuncias-por-corrupcion-fraude-y-malos-manejos-de-empresas-publicas-durante-los-anos-de-evo-morales/|title=Bolivia: Allegations of corruption, fraud and mismanagement of public companies during the years of Evo Morales accumulate|language=es|website=Infobae|date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was elected as the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\n====Initial protest period====\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favorable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> While Morales's first cabinet was majority indigenous (14 out of 16 positions), this number steadily decreased since 2009 and by 2017 contained only three indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2006/01/23/actualidad/1137970802_850215.html|title=Morales toma juramento a los 16 ministros que integran el \"nuevo Gabinete del pueblo\"|work=El Pais|language=es|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=23 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Decree 4078 and repercussions ====\n\nOn 15 November, amid [[2019 Bolivian protests|continuing protests]], violence and [[2019 shortages in Bolivia|shortages]] in several main cities, A\u00f1ez issued Decree 4078 to enlist the police and army to pacify the country. Article 3 of the decree reads \"The personnel of the Armed Forces who participate in operations to restore internal order and public stability will be exempt from criminal liability when, in compliance with their constitutional functions, they acted in legitimate defense or state of necessity, in observance of the principles of legality, absolute necessity and proportionality.\u201d <ref name=HRO>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/17/america/1574014107_965320.html|website=El Pais|language=es|date=17 November 2019|title=Alarm in Bolivia for impunity for the military who repress the protests|author=Francesco Manetto}}</ref> The same day, there was a confrontation close to [[Sacaba]] with pro-Morales supporters, mainly coca growers, while they were attempting to cross a bridge on which a police cordon has been set up. 9 people were killed and 17 injured, 11 of which showing wounds from projectiles. <ref name=sacaba>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/17/gobierno-niega-uso-de-armas-en-sacaba-suman-los-muertos-237622.html|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=17 November 2019|title=Government deny use of arms in Sacaba. The dead increase.}}</ref> Protesters say that they were fired upon without warning while the police report states that 201 people were involved in \"violent acts\" and 10 men were arrested for the \"crimes of armed uprising, possession and carrying of firearms, and manufacture and trade of explosive and suffocating substances\". Several human rights groups, including the [[IACHR]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Human Rights Watch]] and the UN Human Rights Commission, called for the immediate revocation of Decree 4078.<ref name=HRO></ref> Amnesty International described it as a \"carte blanche\" for human rights abuses. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/bolivia-derogar-norma-impunidad-fuerzas-armadas/|date=18 November 2019|title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez must immediately repeal decree giving impunity to Armed Forces personnel|author=Amnesty International}}</ref> Government sources claimed that the bullets were not of the type used by the police while army garrison commander Alfredo Cu\u00e9llar stated that they were under no orders to shoot and would not be authorised to use lethal force in those circumstances. <ref name=sacaba></ref>.\n\nOn 28 November, the controversial decree was repealed by President A\u00f1ez, but not before a further massacre occurred in the [[Senkata]] district of [[El Alto]] in which another 9 people were killed and more injured.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/29/anez-abroga-polemico-decreto-luego-de-la-pacificacion-del-pais-238933.html|language=es|title=A\u00f1ez abrogates controversial decree in order to pacify country|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=IACHR></ref> The Senkata gas refinery plant had been attacked in previous days and a military escort was provided for a convoy of fuel trucks needed to relieve shortages in the cities of El Alto and LA Paz. While en route, a violent clash occurred.<ref name=IACHR></ref>The official government response was, again, that they had not fired shots and that they had been under attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191121/fiscalia-confirma-ocho-fallecidos-por-enfrentamientos-en-senkata|title=Prosecutors office confirm 8 deaths due to clash in Senkata|date=21 November 2019|website=El Alteno|language=es}}</ref> Concerning the deaths, President \u00c1\u00f1ez said \"We deeply regret the deaths of our brothers in El Alto, it hurts us because we are a government of peace\" and called for dialogue to listen to the demands of the protesters. In addition, she asked international organizations and the church to accompany this process in order to stop the violence. \"Let's unite to reconcile, to build the Bolivia for which we are all fighting and so that one Bolivian is never above the other,\" said \u00c1\u00f1ez.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/157419_la-presidenta-jeanine-anez-lamenta-las-muertes-de-el-alto-y-pide-dialogo-para-pacificar-el-pais|website=El Deber|date=December 2019|language=es|title=President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez mourns the deaths of El Alto and calls for dialogue to pacify the country}}</ref>\n\nOn invitation by the state, the IACHR conducted an investigation into the deaths and injuries that occurred during this period of violence. On 10 December they published their preliminary observations, based on interviews conducted with eyewitnesses. The stated that \"it is appropriate to describe these events as massacres, given the number of people who lost their lives in the same way and at the same time and place, and because the acts in question were committed against a specific group of people. Furthermore, the patterns of injuries that have been recorded point strongly to extrajudicial killing practices.\"<ref name=IACHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/iachr/media_center/PReleases/2019/321.asp|date=10 December 2019|website=www.oas.org|title=IACHR Preliminary Findings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/10/cidh-califica-hechos-de-sacaba-senakta-de-masacre-pide-investigacion-internacional-240095.html|date=10 December 2019|language=es|title=IACHR calls acts at Sacaba and Senkata massacres and asks for international investigation|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref> In ongoing talks with families of victims, proposed compensation relating to Decree 4100 includes 100000 Bolivianos ($15000) for families of those killed and from 12500 to 50000 Bolivianos for those injured, the amount depending on severity. By request of the families, the amount is to be given in humanitarian aid (including 12 months of food) rather than a single payment. It also allows the victims to seek help from international organisations. A final agreement has not been reached as there is general mistrust in the government to follow through on their promises. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/2/6/victimas-de-senkata-gobierno-negocian-acuerdo-de-seis-puntos-245777.html|date=6 February 2020|title=Victims of Senkata and government negotiate agreement on 6 points.|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref>\n\n====Later activity====\n\n{{update|talk|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\nHer designated interior minister vowed to \"hunt down\" his predecessor, which reportedly stroked fears of a \"[[witch-hunt]]\" against members of Morales' administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She further stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections {{!}} DW {{!}} 15 November 2019  |last=Welle (www.dw.com) |first=Deutsche |website=DW.COM |language=en-GB |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times. Her government has blamed foreigners for provoking violent clashes during more than a month of post-election violence in [[Bolivia]] that has left dozens of people dead. Police arrested an Argentine national, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz, who is a former member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\n===2020 Presidential Candidacy===\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the center-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/ \u2022 Religion affiliations in Bolivia 2018 | Statista<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nDuring her second senatorial term, \u00c1\u00f1ez was associated with legislative works to combat feminicides and violence against women which has become a continuing theme for her politically.<ref name=CIDOB></ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/100505/1/Revolution_from_Below_in_Bolivia_2_Theory_v4_Full.docx|journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013250 |doi=10.1177/0032329219845944 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after her inauguration, opponents of \u00c1\u00f1ez circulated [[Twitter#Tweets|tweets]] dating back to 2013 <ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref>. These tweets, directed towards indigenous peoples, have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales and an anarcha-feminist and psychologist, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> About \u00c1\u00f1ez, she would later state that \"her hatred of the Indian is of all hatreds the most painful, because it is a hatred of herself\", referring to \u00c1\u00f1ez' own mestizo background. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/opinion/maria-galindo/2019/12/18/jeanine-usurpadora-sustituta-subalterna-240715.html|title=Jeanine: Usurper, substitute, subordinate?|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|author=Mar\u00eda  Galindo|date=18 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has kept [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>[https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado Colocan la bandera de la Flor del Patuj\u00fa junto a la wiphala y la tricolor en Palacio Quemado | EL DEBER<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>[https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html Radio Patuj\u00fa 95.2 FM: IM\u00c1GENES \"POR EL TIPNIS NO\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>[https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios A\u00f1ez viste poncho andino obsequiado por comunarios | Los Tiempos<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 28 January 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez signed a proposed bill to provide cultural recognition to the seven different identities of the country's indigenous women. After signing she stated \"This bill is a demonstration of the value of the [[pollera]] woman as the main character in the fight for the equality of indigenous, rural, migrant and mestizo women\" and that \"the principle of equality must transcend laws and transform society and create more opportunities for indigenous and rural women.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bolivia.com/actualidad/nacionales/cholas-bolivianas-patrimonio-cultural-e-inmaterial-bolivia-jeanine-anez-258189|website=www.bolivia.com|language=es|date=28 January 2020|title=Government will seek to declare the Cholas cultural heritage of Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez was married in Santa Cruz at the age of 23 to Tadeo Ribera Bruckner, a lawyer and a former mayor of [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], the capital of [[Beni Department|Beni]] representing the Uni\u00f3n C\u00edvica Solidaridad (UCS) party. They had two children together, Carolina (born 1990) and Jos\u00e9 Armando (born 1995). Ribera died in [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] on 29 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/164289_fallece-el-exesposo-de-la-presidenta-jeanine-anez|website=El Deber|title=Ex-husband of President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez dies|date=29 January 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n\u00c1\u00f1ez's second husband is H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal, a Colombian from [[Tolima Department|Tolima]]. He is a politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Hincapi\u00e9 ran, unsuccessfully, for a seat in the Colombian Senate in 2018, and as a member of the Tolima regional assembly and House of Representatives in 2010 and 2014 respectively. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafm.com.co/internacional/el-colombiano-que-se-robo-el-corazon-de-la-presidenta-e-de-bolivia|title=The Colombian that stole he heart of the President of Bolivia|language=es|website=www.lafm.com.co|date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Until recently, they travelled between Bolivia and Colombia to see one another, although this has become easier since failure to win a seat in 2018.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.opinion.com.bo/content/print/jeanine-anez-chavez-mujer-dirige-bolivia-afronta-desafios/20191122104634737958|website=www.opinion.com.bo|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who heads Bolivia and faces challenges|language=es|date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = Tadeo Ribera Bruckner (1990-?), H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal (?-present)\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the center-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nJeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez was born in the small Amazonian town of [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]] in the [[Department of Beni]], Bolivia, on 13 August 1967. She was the youngest of seven children born to two teachers.<ref name=biografias>{{cite web|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/bolivien/10697.pdf|language=es|title=BIOGRAF\u00cdAS Historias de Vida en la Asamblea Legislativa Plurinacional|year=2013|page=416\u2013418}}</ref> Her background has been described as poor [[mestiza]] and lower-middle-class.<ref name=\"\u201ceconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=CIDOB>{{cite web|url=https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |website=www.cidob.org|language=es|date=13 December 2019}}</ref> During this time, San Joaqu\u00edn lacked proper roads, was dependent on diesel generators for power and had a water supply that was rationed. Recalling her childhood, she says \"We grew up with many limitations, with many needs but nevertheless I had a beautiful childhood, very free.\" <ref name=biografias></ref>\n\nShe attended the local school, a girls school that her mother would later become director of. At age seventeen, she achieved her baccalaureate and left San Joaqu\u00edn to pursue an education in La Paz, first at the Bolivian Institute and then at the Abraham Lincoln Institute. At this time, she studied to become a secretary.<ref name=biografias></ref> She continued to [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] where she took further studies as a secretary, including computing and some English. <ref name=biografias></ref> After getting married at aged 23, she moved to [[Trinidad, Bolivia]], where she enrolled at the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n and obtained a graduate degree in law and legal sciences.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvisi\u00f3n.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she spoke out against the approval of a finance bill by the Morales' government for the construction of the Villa Tunari-San Ignacio de Moxos highway. She claimed that it was not approved with due consideration for the native peoples and institutions of the region saying that \"indigenous people's right was violated\", a sentiment echoed by leader of the natives of the Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park Indigenous Territory (TIPNIS), Adolfo Moye who said it was enacted \"without considering the serious impact on the ecosystem and natural reserves of the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20110511/senadora-cuestiona-financiamiento-carretera-cochabamba-beni|title=Senator questions financing of Cochabamba-Beni highway|language=es|date=11 May 2011|website=www.losttiempos.com|}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, A\u00f1ez and fellow party legislator Adri\u00e1n Oliva presented a report to the Human Rights Commission of the Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay in an effort to publicise human rights violations in Bolivia. According to the UN refugee office, UNHCR, there were around 600 Bolivian exiles or refugees, a hundred political prisoners and at least 15 cases of torture at this time. The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights stated that there was a \"crisis in the administration of justice\" in Bolivia. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120523/presentan-informe-uruguay|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=23 May 2012|language=es|title=Report presented in Uruguay}}</ref> Also in 2012, A\u00f1ez was selected as a Bolivian representative to the Amazonian Parliament. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120316/senado-designo-representantes-parlamentos-internacionales|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=16 March 2012|language=es|title=Senate designates representatives to international parliaments.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, there were a series of nationwide strikes and protests against the MAS government concerning the reduction of seats in the Chamber of Deputies for the areas of [[Department of Beni|Beni]], [[Potos\u00ed department|Potos\u00ed]] and [[Department of Chuquisaca|Chuquisaca]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/2/beni-potosi-inician-paro-contra-escanos-2058.html|date=2 October 2013}}</ref>As Senator of Beni, Jeanine A\u00f1ez joined picket lines and was among six legistlators and a dozen indigenous representatives of [[CONAMAQ]] that went on hunger strike in protest to the legistlation being passed by the MAS majority in both chambers. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/conflicto-escanos-agrava-tres-piquetes-huelguistas-2255.html|title=Conflict over seats worsens, there are three pickets of strikers|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/opositores-bolivianos-inician-huelga-hambre-contra-reduccion-escanos-2289.html|title=Bolivian opposition members start hunger strike against reduction of seats|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, \u00c1\u00f1ez made complaints about the lack of financial transparency from the government. Requests for reports as part of opposition legislators ability to audit the activities of the state were delayed and in 499 out of 1979 cases for the 2013-14 period received no response. The authorities, according to the regulations of the Chamber of Deputies, were permitted 10 business days to respond to a request for a report, and in the Senate, 15 days. If the request for a written report is not answered, an injunction can be issued to give a time limit of 48 hours. \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases, these injunctions were ignored and there was a \"denial of information\". Many of the projects had multi-million budgets with several interested parties for whom access is even more restricted.  \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases which do receive replies \"they are responses without response\". Responses included two sheets of photocopies, material unrelated to the request or boxes full of documents which do \"not intend to clarify the doubts, but to hinder the work of the legislators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2014/2/9/denuncian-trabas-acceso-informacion-para-fiscalizar-13544.html|title=They denounce obstacles in access to information for auditing|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> In 2019-2020, many of these cases are under investigation. <ref name=corruption>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/22/bolivia-se-suman-denuncias-por-corrupcion-fraude-y-malos-manejos-de-empresas-publicas-durante-los-anos-de-evo-morales/|title=Bolivia: Allegations of corruption, fraud and mismanagement of public companies during the years of Evo Morales accumulate|language=es|website=Infobae|date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was elected as the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\n====Initial protest period====\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favorable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> While Morales's first cabinet was majority indigenous (14 out of 16 positions), this number steadily decreased since 2009 and by 2017 contained only three indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2006/01/23/actualidad/1137970802_850215.html|title=Morales toma juramento a los 16 ministros que integran el \"nuevo Gabinete del pueblo\"|work=El Pais|language=es|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=23 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Decree 4078 and repercussions ====\n\nOn 15 November, amid [[2019 Bolivian protests|continuing protests]], violence and [[2019 shortages in Bolivia|shortages]] in several main cities, A\u00f1ez issued Decree 4078 to enlist the police and army to pacify the country. Article 3 of the decree reads \"The personnel of the Armed Forces who participate in operations to restore internal order and public stability will be exempt from criminal liability when, in compliance with their constitutional functions, they acted in legitimate defense or state of necessity, in observance of the principles of legality, absolute necessity and proportionality.\u201d <ref name=HRO>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/17/america/1574014107_965320.html|website=El Pais|language=es|date=17 November 2019|title=Alarm in Bolivia for impunity for the military who repress the protests|author=Francesco Manetto}}</ref> The same day, there was a confrontation close to [[Sacaba]] with pro-Morales supporters, mainly coca growers, while they were attempting to cross a bridge on which a police cordon has been set up. 9 people were killed and 17 injured, 11 of which showing wounds from projectiles. <ref name=sacaba>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/17/gobierno-niega-uso-de-armas-en-sacaba-suman-los-muertos-237622.html|website}}</ref> Protesters say that they were fired upon without warning while the police report states that 201 people were involved in \"violent acts\" and 10 men were arrested for the \"crimes of armed uprising, possession and carrying of firearms, and manufacture and trade of explosive and suffocating substances\". Several human rights groups, including the [[IACHR]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Human Rights Watch]] and the UN Human Rights Commission, called for the immediate revocation of Decree 4078. <ref name=HRO></ref> Amnesty International described it as a \"carte blanche\" for human rights abuses. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/bolivia-derogar-norma-impunidad-fuerzas-armadas/|date=18 November 2019|title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez must immediately repeal decree giving impunity to Armed Forces personnel|auhor=Amnesty International</ref> Government sources claimed that the bullets were not of the type used by the police while army garrison commander Alfredo Cu\u00e9llar stated that they were under no orders to shoot and would not be authorised to use lethal force in those circumstances. <ref name=sacaba></ref>.\n\nOn 28 November, the controversial decree was repealed by President A\u00f1ez, but not before a further massacre occurred in the [[Senkata]] district of [[El Alto]] in which another 9 people were killed and more injured. <ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/29/anez-abroga-polemico-decreto-luego-de-la-pacificacion-del-pais-238933.html|language=es|title=A\u00f1ez abrogates controversial decree in order to pacify country|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=IACHR></ref> The Senkata gas refinery plant had been attacked in previous days and a military escort was provided for a convoy of fuel trucks needed to relieve shortages in the cities of El Alto and LA Paz. While en route, a violent clash occurred. <ref name=IACHR></ref>The official government response was, again, that they had not fired shots and that they had been under attack. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191121/fiscalia-confirma-ocho-fallecidos-por-enfrentamientos-en-senkata|Prosecutors office confirm 8 deaths due to clash in Senkata|date=21 November 2019|website=El Alteno|language=es}}</ref> Concerning the deaths, President \u00c1\u00f1ez said \" We deeply regret the deaths of our brothers in El Alto, it hurts us because we are a government of peace\" and called for dialogue to listen to the demands of the protesters. In addition, she asked international organizations and the church to accompany this process in order to stop the violence. \"Let's unite to reconcile, to build the Bolivia for which we are all fighting and so that one Bolivian is never above the other,\" said \u00c1\u00f1ez.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/157419_la-presidenta-jeanine-anez-lamenta-las-muertes-de-el-alto-y-pide-dialogo-para-pacificar-el-pais|website=El Deber|date=December 2019|language=es|title=President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez mourns the deaths of El Alto and calls for dialogue to pacify the country}}</ref>\n\nOn invitation by the state, the IACHR conducted an investigation into the deaths and injuries that occurred during this period of violence. On 10 December they published their preliminary observations, based on interviews conducted with eyewitnesses. The stated that \"it is appropriate to describe these events as massacres, given the number of people who lost their lives in the same way and at the same time and place, and because the acts in question were committed against a specific group of people. Furthermore, the patterns of injuries that have been recorded point strongly to extrajudicial killing practices.\"<ref name=IACHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/iachr/media_center/PReleases/2019/321.asp|date=10 December 2019|website=www.oas.org|title=The IACHR presents its preliminary observations following its visit to Bolivia and requests an urgent international investigation take place into the serious human rights violations that have occurred in the country since the October 2019 elections}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/10/cidh-califica-hechos-de-sacaba-senakta-de-masacre-pide-investigacion-internacional-240095.html|date=10 December 2019|language=es|title=IACHR calls acts at Sacaba and Senkata massacres and asks for international investigation|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref> In ongoing talks with families of victims, proposed compensation relating to Decree 4100 includes 100000 Bolivianos ($15000) for families of those killed and from 12500 to 50000 Bolivianos for those injured, the amount depending on severity. By request of the families, the amount is to be given in humanitarian aid (including 12 months of food) rather than a single payment. It also allows the victims to seek help from international organisations. A final agreement has not been reached as there is general mistrust in the government to follow through on their promises. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/2/6/victimas-de-senkata-gobierno-negocian-acuerdo-de-seis-puntos-245777.html|date=6 February 2020|title=Victims of Senkata and government negotiate agreement on 6 points.|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref>\n\n====Later activity====\n\n{{update|talk|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\nHer designated interior minister vowed to \"hunt down\" his predecessor, which reportedly stroked fears of a \"[[witch-hunt]]\" against members of Morales' administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She further stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections {{!}} DW {{!}} 15 November 2019  |last=Welle (www.dw.com) |first=Deutsche |website=DW.COM |language=en-GB |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times. Her government has blamed foreigners for provoking violent clashes during more than a month of post-election violence in [[Bolivia]] that has left dozens of people dead. Police arrested an Argentine national, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz, who is a former member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\n===2020 Presidential Candidacy===\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the center-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/ \u2022 Religion affiliations in Bolivia 2018 | Statista<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nDuring her second senatorial term, \u00c1\u00f1ez was associated with legislative works to combat feminicides and violence against women which has become a continuing theme for her politically.<ref name=CIDOB></ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/100505/1/Revolution_from_Below_in_Bolivia_2_Theory_v4_Full.docx|journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013250 |doi=10.1177/0032329219845944 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after her inauguration, opponents of \u00c1\u00f1ez circulated [[Twitter#Tweets|tweets]] dating back to 2013 <ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref>. These tweets, directed towards indigenous peoples, have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales and an anarcha-feminist and psychologist, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> About \u00c1\u00f1ez, she would later state that \"her hatred of the Indian is of all hatreds the most painful, because it is a hatred of herself\", referring to \u00c1\u00f1ez' own mestizo background. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/opinion/maria-galindo/2019/12/18/jeanine-usurpadora-sustituta-subalterna-240715.html|title=Jeanine: Usurper, substitute, subordinate?|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|author=Mar\u00eda  Galindo|date=18 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has kept [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>[https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado Colocan la bandera de la Flor del Patuj\u00fa junto a la wiphala y la tricolor en Palacio Quemado | EL DEBER<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>[https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html Radio Patuj\u00fa 95.2 FM: IM\u00c1GENES \"POR EL TIPNIS NO\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>[https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios A\u00f1ez viste poncho andino obsequiado por comunarios | Los Tiempos<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 28 January 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez signed a proposed bill to provide cultural recognition to the seven different identities of the country's indigenous women. After signing she stated \"This bill is a demonstration of the value of the [[pollera]] woman as the main character in the fight for the equality of indigenous, rural, migrant and mestizo women\" and that \"the principle of equality must transcend laws and transform society and create more opportunities for indigenous and rural women.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bolivia.com/actualidad/nacionales/cholas-bolivianas-patrimonio-cultural-e-inmaterial-bolivia-jeanine-anez-258189|website=www.bolivia.com|language=es|date=28 January 2020|title=Government will seek to declare the Cholas cultural heritage of Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez was married in Santa Cruz at the age of 23 to Tadeo Ribera Bruckner, a lawyer and a former mayor of [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], the capital of [[Beni Department|Beni]] representing the Uni\u00f3n C\u00edvica Solidaridad (UCS) party. They had two children together, Carolina (born 1990) and Jos\u00e9 Armando (born 1995). Ribera died in [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] on 29 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/164289_fallece-el-exesposo-de-la-presidenta-jeanine-anez|website=El Deber|title=Ex-husband of President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez dies|date=29 January 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n\u00c1\u00f1ez's second husband is H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal, a Colombian from [[Tolima Department|Tolima]]. He is a politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Hincapi\u00e9 ran, unsuccessfully, for a seat in the Colombian Senate in 2018, and as a member of the Tolima regional assembly and House of Representatives in 2010 and 2014 respectively. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafm.com.co/internacional/el-colombiano-que-se-robo-el-corazon-de-la-presidenta-e-de-bolivia|title=The Colombian that stole he heart of the President of Bolivia|language=es|website=www.lafm.com.co|date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Until recently, they travelled between Bolivia and Colombia to see one another, although this has become easier since failure to win a seat in 2018.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.opinion.com.bo/content/print/jeanine-anez-chavez-mujer-dirige-bolivia-afronta-desafios/20191122104634737958|website=www.opinion.com.bo|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who heads Bolivia and faces challenges|language=es|date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "name_user": "Crmoorhead", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDecree 4078 and repercussions:ref fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeanine_%C3%81%C3%B1ez"}
{"title_page": "Quadcopter", "text_new": "[[File:Quadcopter camera drone in flight.jpg|thumb|A [[DJI (company)|DJI]] [[Phantom (UAV)|Phantom]] quadcopter [[unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] in flight]]\n\nA '''quadcopter,''' also called a '''quadrotor helicopter''' or '''quadrotor''',<ref name=\"dasc04\"/> is a [[multirotor]] [[helicopter]] that is lifted and propelled by four [[Helicopter rotor|rotors]]. Quadcopters are classified as [[rotorcraft]], as opposed to [[fixed-wing aircraft]], because their [[Lift (force)|lift]] is generated by a set of [[helicopter rotor|rotors]] (vertically oriented [[propeller]]s).\n\nQuadcopters generally use two pairs of identical fixed pitch propellers; two [[clockwise]] (CW) and two [[counterclockwise]] (CCW). These use independent variation of the speed of each rotor to achieve control. By changing the speed of each rotor it is possible to specifically generate a desired total [[thrust]]; to locate for the [[centre of thrust]] both laterally and longitudinally; and to create a desired total [[torque]], or turning force.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stafford |first=Jesse|url=http://ffden-2.phys.uaf.edu/webproj/212_spring_2014/Clay_Allen/clay_allen/works.html |title=How a Quadcopter works &#124; Clay Allen  |publisher=University of Alaska, Fairbanks |date=Spring 2014 |accessdate=2015-01-20}}</ref>\n\nQuadcopters differ from conventional helicopters, which use rotors that are able to vary the pitch of their blades dynamically as they move around the rotor hub. In the early days of flight, quadcopters (then referred to either as 'quadrotors' or simply as 'helicopters') were seen as possible solutions to some of the persistent problems in vertical flight. Torque-induced control issues (as well as efficiency issues originating from the [[tail rotor]], which generates no useful lift) can be eliminated by counter-rotation, and the relatively short blades are much easier to construct. A number of manned designs appeared in the 1920s and 1930s. These vehicles were among the first successful heavier-than-air [[VTOL|vertical take off and landing (VTOL)]] vehicles.<ref name=\"leishman00\">{{cite book | last = Leishman | first = J.G. | title = Principles of Helicopter Aerodynamics | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2000 | location = New York, NY | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nMV-TkaX-9cC&pg=PA688&lpg=PA688&dq=Leishman,+J.G.+%282000%29.+Principles+of+Helicopter+Aerodynamics.#v=snippet&q=quadrotor&f=false| isbn = 9780521858601 }}</ref>  However, early prototypes suffered from poor performance,<ref name=\"leishman00\" /> and latter prototypes required too much pilot work load, due to poor stability augmentation<ref name=\"anderson81\">{{Cite journal | last = Anderson | first = S.B. | title = Historical Overview of V/STOL Aircraft Technology | journal = NASA Technical Memorandum 81280 | year = 1997 | url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20020051099&hterms=81280&qs=N%3D0%26Ntk%3DAll%26Ntt%3D81280%26Ntx%3Dmode%2520matchallpartial%26Nm%3D17%7CCollection%7CNACA%7C%7C123%7CCollection%7CNASA%2520STI}}</ref> and limited control authority.\n\nAround 2005 to 2010, advances in electronics allowed the production of cheap lightweight flight controllers, [[accelerometer]]s ([[Inertial measurement unit|IMU]]), [[global positioning systems|global positioning system]] and cameras. This resulted in the quadcopter configuration becoming popular for small [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s.  With their small size and maneuverability, these quadcopters can be flown indoors as well as outdoors.<ref name=\"dasc04\">{{cite conference | first = G.M. | last = Hoffmann |author2=Rajnarayan, D.G. |author3=Waslander, S.L. |author4=Dostal, D. |author5=Jang, J.S. |author6=Tomlin, C.J. | title = The Stanford Testbed of Autonomous Rotorcraft for Multi Agent Control (STARMAC) | booktitle = In the Proceedings of the 23rd Digital Avionics System Conference | pages = 12.E.4/1\u201310 | date = November 2004 | location = Salt Lake City, UT | doi = 10.1109/DASC.2004.1390847 }}</ref><ref name=\"b\u00fcchi11\">{{cite book| last = B\u00fcchi | first = Roland | title = Fascination Quadrocopter | year = 2011 | location = |isbn=978-3-8423-6731-9 }}</ref>\n\nAt a small size, quadcopters are cheaper and more durable than conventional helicopters due to their mechanical simplicity.<ref name=\"acra2006\">{{cite conference | first = P. | last = Pounds |author2=Mahony, R. |author3=Corke, P.  | title = Modelling and Control of a Quad-Rotor Robot | booktitle = In the Proceedings of the Australasian Conference on Robotics and Automation | date = December 2006 | location = Auckland, New Zealand | url = http://www.araa.asn.au/acra/acra2006/papers/paper_5_26.pdf }}</ref> Their smaller blades are also advantageous because they possess less kinetic energy, reducing their ability to cause damage. For small-scale quadcopters, this makes the vehicles safer for close interaction. It is also possible to fit quadcopters with guards that enclose the rotors, further reducing the potential for damage.<ref name=\"hoffmanAugust2007\">{{cite conference | first = G. | last = Hoffman | author2 = Huang, H. | author3 = Waslander, S.L. | author4 = Tomlin, C.J. | title = Quadrotor Helicopter Flight Dynamics and Control: Theory and Experiment | booktitle = In the Conference of the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics | date = 20\u201323 August 2007 | location = Hilton Head, South Carolina | url = http://hoffmann.stanford.edu/papers/Quadrotor_Dynamics_GNC07.pdf | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100813162324/http://hoffmann.stanford.edu/papers/Quadrotor_Dynamics_GNC07.pdf | archivedate = 13 August 2010 }}</ref> However, as size increases, fixed propeller quadcopters develop disadvantages relative to conventional helicopters. Increasing blade size increases their momentum. This means that changes in blade speed take longer, which negatively impacts control. Helicopters do not experience this problem as increasing the size of the rotor disk does not significantly impact the ability to control blade pitch.\n\nDue to their ease of construction and control, quadcopter aircraft are frequently used as amateur [[model aircraft]] projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/01/how-to-quadrocopter-based-on-arduin.html|title=How-To: Quadrocopter based on Arduino|work=MAKE|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ng.uavp.ch/moin/FrontPage|title=FrontPage - UAVP-NG - The Open Source Next Generation Multicopter|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early attempts===\n; [[Breguet-Richet Gyroplane]] (1907)\n:A four-rotor helicopter designed by [[Louis Breguet]]. This was the first rotary wing aircraft to lift itself off the ground, although only in tethered flight at an altitude of a few feet. In 1908 it was reported as having flown 'several times', although details are sparse.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |last=Young\n  |first=Warren R.\n  |title=The Helicopters\n  |work=The Epic of Flight\n  |location=Chicago\n  |publisher=Time-Life Books\n  |year=1982\n  |isbn=978-0-8094-3350-6\n  |page=[https://archive.org/details/helicopters00youn/page/28 28]\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/helicopters00youn/page/28\n  }}</ref>\n\n;Oehmichen No.2  (1920)\n:[[Etienne Oehmichen]] experimented with rotorcraft designs in the 1920s.  Among the six designs he tried, his helicopter No.2 had four rotors and eight propellers, all driven by a single engine.  The Oehmichen No.2 used a steel-tube frame, with two-bladed rotors at the ends of the four arms. The angle of these blades could be varied by warping. Five of the propellers, spinning in the horizontal plane, stabilized the machine laterally.  Another propeller was mounted at the nose for steering.  The remaining pair of propellers functioned as its forward propulsion. The aircraft exhibited a considerable degree of stability and increase in control-accuracy for its time, and made over a thousand test flights during the middle 1920s. By 1923 it was able to remain airborne for several minutes at a time, and on April 14, 1924 it established the first-ever FAI distance record for helicopters of {{convert|360|m|yd|abbr=on}}. It demonstrated the ability to complete a circular course<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1924/1924%20-%200047.html \"A Successful French Helicopter\" ]''Flight'' 24 January 1924 p47</ref> and later, it completed the first {{convert|1|km|mi}} closed-circuit flight by a rotorcraft.\n\n[[File:De Bothezat Quadrotor.jpg|thumb|[[de Bothezat helicopter]], 1923 photo]]\n\n;[[de Bothezat helicopter]] (1922)\n:[[George de Bothezat|Dr. George de Bothezat]] and Ivan Jerome developed this aircraft, with six-bladed rotors at the end of an X-shaped structure.  Two small propellers with variable pitch were used for thrust and yaw control.  The vehicle used collective pitch control. Built by the US Air Service, it made its first flight in October 1922. About 100 flights were made by the end of 1923.  The highest it ever reached was about {{convert|5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. Although demonstrating feasibility, it was underpowered, unresponsive, mechanically complex and susceptible to reliability problems. Pilot workload was too high during hover to attempt lateral motion.\n\n;[[Convertawings Model A Quadrotor]] (1956)\n:This unique helicopter was intended to be the prototype for a line of much larger civil and military quadrotor helicopters. The design featured two engines driving four rotors through a system of v belts. No tail rotor was needed and control was obtained by varying the thrust between rotors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1956/1956%20-%201564.html|title=1956 - 1564 - Flight Archive|work=flightglobal.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Flown successfully many times in the mid-1950s, this helicopter proved the quadrotor design and it was also the first four-rotor helicopter to demonstrate successful forward flight. Due to a lack of orders for commercial or military versions however, the project was terminated. Convertawings proposed a Model E that would have a maximum weight of {{convert|42000|lb|t|abbr=on}} with a payload of {{convert|10900|lb|t|abbr=on}} over 300 miles and at up to {{convert|173|mph|abbr=on}}. The Hanson Elastic Articulated (EA) bearingless rotor grew out of work done in the early 1960s at Lockheed California by Thomas F. Hanson, who had previously worked at Convertawings on the quadrotor's rotor design and control system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US3261407|title=Patent US3261407 - Helicopter rotor system|work=google.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GgntoJiYek4C&pg=PA157&lpg=PA157&dq=Hanson+Elastic+Articulated+Rotor#v=onepage&q=Hanson%20Elastic%20Articulated%20Rotor&f=false|title=The Seventh International Conference on Vibration Problems ICOVP 2005|accessdate=13 March 2015|isbn=9781402054013|last1=Inan|first1=Esin|last2=Kiris|first2=Ahmet|date=2007-01-20}}</ref>\n\n;[[Curtiss-Wright VZ-7]] (1958)\n:The Curtiss-Wright VZ-7 was a [[VTOL]] aircraft designed by the [[Curtiss-Wright]] company for the US Army. The VZ-7 was controlled by changing the thrust of each of the four propellers. Two VZ-7 prototypes were created and both performed adequately during the initial flight test program, and both did reasonably well when evaluated by the Army. The VZ-7 was capable of hovering and forward flight and proved relatively stable and easy to operate. The aircraft was retired in 1960 due to not meeting military standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buybestquadcopter.com/history-future-drones/|title=A brief history of drones \u2013 Plus a sneak peek into the future|last=Nel|first=Ruaan|date=26 February 2019|access-date=13 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Recent developments===\nIn the last few decades, small-scale [[unmanned aerial vehicles]] have been used for many applications. The need for aircraft with greater maneuverability and hovering ability has led to a rise in quadcopter research. The four-rotor design allows quadcopters to be relatively simple in design yet highly reliable and maneuverable. Research is continuing to increase the abilities of quadcopters by making advances in multi-craft communication, environment exploration, and maneuverability. If these developing qualities can be combined, quadcopters would be capable of advanced autonomous missions that are currently not possible with other vehicles.<ref name=\"illumin\">{{cite web|url=http://illumin.usc.edu/162/the-quadrotors-coming-of-age|title=Illumin - The Quadrotor's Coming of Age|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome current programs include:\n\n* The [[Bell Boeing Quad TiltRotor]] concept takes the fixed quadcopter concept further by combining it with the tilt rotor concept for a proposed C-130 sized military transport.\n[[File:Ardrone-img5-front.jpg|thumb|right|Flying prototype of the [[Parrot AR.Drone]] ]]\n[[File:Parrot AR.Drone 2.0 take-off, Nevada.jpg|thumb|[[Parrot AR.Drone]] 2.0 take-off, Nevada, 2012]]\n* [[AeroQuad]] and [[ArduCopter]] are [[open-source hardware]] and software projects based on Arduino for the DIY construction of quadcopters.<ref name=\"AeroQuad\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.slashgear.com/diy-quadrocopters-quaduino-ng-and-aeroquad-videos-1369771/|title = DIY Quadrocopters: Quaduino NG and AeroQuad [Videos]|accessdate = 4 February 2012|last = Davies|first = Chris|date = 13 January 2010| work = SlashGear}}</ref><ref name=\"Make Magazine\">{{cite web|title=ArduCopter 3D Robotics Quadcopter|url=http://kits.makezine.com/2011/11/12/arducopter-3dr-quadcopter/|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Nixie drone|Nixie]] is a small camera-equipped drone that can be worn as a wrist band.<ref name=Nixie-site>{{cite web|title=Official Nixie website|url=http://www.flynixie.com|publisher=Nixie|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=TechCrunch-28Sep14>{{cite news|last1=Kumparak|first1=Greg|title=A wearable drone that launches off your wrist to take your selfie|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/09/28/a-wearable-drone-that-launches-off-your-wrist-to-take-your-selfie|work=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=11 October 2014|date=28 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=Forbes-29Sep14>{{cite web|last1=Monckton|first1=Paul|title=Nixie, the wearable selfie drone|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulmonckton/2014/09/29/nixie-the-wearable-selfie-drone|publisher=[[Forbes]]: Life|accessdate=8 October 2014|date=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Airbus]] is developing a battery-powered quadcopter to act as an urban air taxi, at first with a pilot but potentially autonomous in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2017/10/05/airbus-on-track-to-fly-its-electric-aerial-taxi-in-2018/|title=Airbus on track to fly its electric aerial taxi in 2018}}</ref>\nSeveral camera-drone projects have turned into high-profile commercial failures:\n* [[Zano (drone)]]{{snd}} a high-profile [[Kickstarter]] project to build a quadcopter-camera drone, Zano failed after delivering only a small fraction of their orders in a partially nonfunctional state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/biggest-kickstarter-and-indiegogo-scams/|title=Best laid plans of mobs and men: The 5 biggest crowdfunding failures of all time|date=28 July 2016|work=digitaltrends.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/the-9-most-disgraceful-crowdfunding-failures-of-2015-1747957776|title=The 9 Most Disgraceful Crowdfunding Failures of 2015|first=Kate|last=Knibbs|work=gizmodo.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lily Robotics, Inc.|Lily Camera]]{{snd}} a startup attempting to make a quadcopter-camera drone, sued by the San Francisco District Attorney after they closed down without fulfilling any of their pre-orders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-38595473|title=Drone company Lily shuts down owing $34m|work=BBC News|date=12 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/much-hyped-lily-camera-drone-is-out-of-business/|title=Much-hyped Lily Camera Drone going out of business|work=cnet.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2017/01/13/lawsuit-killed-lily-robotics-drones/|title=How An Allegedly Fake Video Killed A Much-Hyped Drone Startup|first=Ryan|last=Mac|work=forbes.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a video was posted on [[YouTube]] of an airborne quadcopter firing a pistol four times in a wooded area, sparking regulatory concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/16/drone-firing-handgun-video-youtube|title=Drone firing handgun appears in video|author=Samuel Gibbs|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=20 July 2015|date=2015-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestack.com/drone-firing-gun-160715|title=A drone firing a gun: so this is what all the regulation is about|work=thestack.com|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n{{See also|Unmanned aerial vehicle#Applications}}\n[[File:Quadcopter landing at Head of the Charles.agr.jpg|thumb|A quadcopter being recovered after photographing the [[Head of the Charles]] regatta in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] ]]\n\n===Research platform===\nQuadcopters are a useful tool for university researchers to test and evaluate new ideas in a number of different fields, including [[flight control]] theory, [[Air navigation|navigation]], [[Real-time computing|real time systems]], and [[robotics]]. In recent years many universities have shown quadcopters performing increasingly complex aerial manoeuvres. Swarms of quadcopters can hover in mid-air,<ref>Saska, M.; Vakula, J.; Preucil, L. [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286680349_Swarms_of_micro_aerial_vehicles_stabilized_under_a_visual_relative_localization Swarms of Micro Aerial Vehicles Stabilized Under a Visual Relative Localization]. In ICRA2014: Proceedings of 2014 IEEE International Conference on Robotics and Automation. 2014.</ref><ref>Saska, M. MAV-swarms: unmanned aerial vehicles stabilized along a given path using onboard relative localization. In Proceedings of 2015 International Conference on Unmanned Aircraft Systems (ICUAS). 2015</ref><ref>Bennet, D. J.; McInnes, C. R. [https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/13623/1/McInnes_CR_-_strathprints_-_Verifiable_control_of_a_swarm_of_unmanned_aerial_vehicles_23_Nov_09.pdf Verifiable control of a swarm of unmanned aerial vehicles]. Journal of Aerospace Engineering, vol. 223, no. 7, pp. 939\u2013953, 2009.</ref><ref>Saska, M.; Chudoba, J.; Preucil, L.; Thomas, J.; Loianno, G.; Tresnak, A.; Vonasek, V.; Kumar, V. [https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/6842301/ Autonomous Deployment of Swarms of Micro-Aerial Vehicles in Cooperative Surveillance]. In Proceedings of 2014 International Conference on Unmanned Aircraft Systems (ICUAS). 2014.</ref> fly in formations,<ref>Saska, M.; Kasl, Z.; Preucil, L. [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/a8b2/b317e16e609d0478dbbe339fac2760bda4a4.pdf Motion Planning and Control of Formations of Micro Aerial Vehicles]. In Proceedings of the 19th World Congress of the International Federation of Automatic Control. 2014.</ref><ref>Barnes, L.; Garcia, R.; Fields, M.; Valavanis, K. [http://people.virginia.edu/~lb3dp/resources/pubs/iros-swarm-08.pdf Swarm formation control utilizing ground and aerial unmanned systems], in IEEE/RSJ International Conference on Intelligent Robots and Systems. 2008.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Coordination and navigation of heterogeneous UAVs-UGVs teams localized by a hawk-eye approach <!-- - IEEE Conference Publication -->|authors=Saska, M.; Vonasek, V.; Krajnik, T.; Preucil, L.|journal=In Proceedings of 2012 IEEE/RSJ International Conference on Intelligent Robots and Systems<!--|website=ieeexplore.ieee.org-->|date=October 7\u201312, 2012|doi=10.1109/IROS.2012.6385517}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saska|first=Martin|last2=Von\u00e1sek|first2=Vojt\u011bch|last3=Krajn\u00edk|first3=Tom\u00e1\u0161|last4=P\u0159eu\u010dil|first4=Libor|date=September 2014 <!--2014-09-01-->|title=Coordination and navigation of heterogeneous MAV\u2013UGV formations localized by a 'hawk-eye'-like approach under a model predictive control scheme|journal=The International Journal of Robotics Research|volume=33|issue=10|pages=1393\u20131412|doi=10.1177/0278364914530482|issn=0278-3649|url=http://eprints.lincoln.ac.uk/14891/1/formations_2014_IJRR.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=September 2011 <!--2011-09-01-->|title=Cascade-type guidance law design for multiple-UAV formation keeping|journal=Aerospace Science and Technology|volume=15|issue=6|pages=431\u2013439|doi=10.1016/j.ast.2010.08.011|issn=1270-9638|authors=No, T.S.; Kim, Y.; Tahk, M.J.; Jeon, G.E.}}</ref> and autonomously perform complex flying routines such as flips, darting through [[hula]] hoops and organising themselves to fly through windows as a group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/grasp-nano-quadrotor-robots-swarm/21302/|title=UPenn's GRASP lab unleashes a swarm of Nano Quadrotors|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2012-02-02}}</ref>\n\nThere are numerous advantages to using quadcopters as versatile test platforms. They are relatively cheap, available in a variety of sizes and their simple mechanical design means that they can be built and maintained by amateurs. Due to the multi-disciplinary nature of operating a quadcopter, academics from a number of fields need to work together in order to make significant improvements to the way quadcopters perform. Quadcopter projects are typically collaborations between computer science, electrical engineering and mechanical engineering specialists.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.asee-ncs.org/proceedings/2015/Paper%20files/Student_Papers/2015_ASEE_NCS_Conference_submission_26.pdf|title = Semi-Autonomous Gesture Controlled UAV Transportation System|accessdate = 18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Military and law enforcement===\nQuadcopter unmanned aerial vehicles are used for surveillance and reconnaissance by military and law enforcement agencies, as well as search and rescue missions in urban environments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/military/planes-uavs/armed-quadrotors-are-coming-10720086|title=Armed Quadrotors Are Coming|work=Popular Mechanics|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2012-07-16}}</ref> One such example is the [[Aeryon Scout]], created by Canadian company [[Aeryon Labs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeryon.com|title=Aeryon Labs Inc.|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> which is a small UAV that can quietly hover in place and use a camera to observe people and objects on the ground. The company claims that the quadrotor played a key role in a drug raid in Central America by providing visual surveillance of a [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficker's]] compound deep in the jungle (Aeryon has declined to name the exact country and provide other specific details).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/automaton/robotics/military-robots/aeryon-scout-quadrotor-spies-on-bad-guys-from-above|title=Aeryon Scout Quadrotor Spies On Bad Guys From Above|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe weaponization of drones is now a huge concern to the wider security industry, as is their use to disrupt airspace, as seen at Gatwick Airport in the UK in December 2018,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47919680|title=Gatwick drone attack possible inside job, say police|accessdate=9 July 2019|work=BBC News|date=2019-04-14|last1=Rowlatt|first1=Justin}}</ref> prompting the United Kingdom\u2019s Civil Aviation Authority, via Parliament to make expedient changes to UK drone laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47299805|title=Drone no-fly zone to be widened after Gatwick chaos|accessdate=9 July 2019|work=BBC News|date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nAfter a recreational quadcopter (or \"drone\") crashed on the [[White House]] lawn early in the morning of January 26, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-drones-white-house-20150126-story.html|title=Drone crashes at White House; its operator contacts Secret Service|author=Los Angeles Times|date=26 January 2015|work=latimes.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] began a series of test flights of such equipment in order to fashion a security protocol against hostile quadcopters.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/news/nation/secret-service-testing-drones-to-defend-white-house/2220819 Secret Service Testing Drones In Bid To Defend White House], Associated Press, March 10, 2015</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Mosul (2016\u201317)|Battle of Mosul]] it was reported that commercially available quadcopters and drones were being used by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) as surveillance and weapons delivery platforms using improvised cradles to drop grenades and other explosives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/20161012_drone_attacks.html|title=Weaponized Mini-Drones Entering the Fight|last=Eshel |first=Tamir|date=12 October 2016|website=[[Defense Update]]|access-date=25 February 2017|quote=}}</ref> The ISIL drone facility became a target of Royal Air Force strike aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/20170117_drones_attacked.html|title=RAF Strikes Daesh Drone Facility in Mosul |last=Eshel|first=Tamir |date=17 January 2017|website=[[Defense Update]] |access-date=25 February 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Photography===\n[[File:DJI Phantom 4 in Flight March 2016.jpg|thumb|2016 model DJI Phantom 4 quadcopter with a gimbal stabilised 4K UHD camera, GPS stabilization and automatic obstacle avoidance]]\nThe largest use of quadcopters in the USA has been in the field of aerial imagery. Quadcopter UAVs are suitable for this job because of their autonomous nature and huge cost savings.<ref name=\"illumin\"/> \nDrones have also been used for [[light-painting]] photography.<ref>{{cite web|title=Long-Exposure Photos Capture Light Art with Drones in New Mexico|url=https://thecreatorsproject.vice.com/blog/lee-montgomery-light-art-drones-new-mexico-50statesofart|publisher=The Creators Project|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UAS maker creates world's first drone light paintings with a holiday theme|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/drone-light-painting/|publisher=Digital Trends|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=18 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=On Falcon, On Phantom! Drones Draw Holiday 'Light Paintings' in the Sky|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/innovation/falcon-phantom-drones-draw-holiday-light-paintings-sky-n482056|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Journalism===\n{{Main|Drone journalism}}\nIn 2014 The Guardian reported that major media outlets have started to put serious effort into exploring the use of drones for reporting and verifying news on events that include floods, protests and wars.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haddou|first1=Leila|title=Journalism gets into the act as drones capture floods, protests and wars|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/media-blog/2014/feb/12/journalism-drone-capture-floods-protests-wars|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome media outlets and newspapers are using drones to capture photography of celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/videos/0_tzpaidnx/|title=Paparazzi Agency -- We've Used Drones For A Long Time|work=www.tmz.com|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Drone-delivery===\n{{Main|Delivery drone}}\nIn December 2013, the [[Deutsche Post]] gathered international media attention with the project Parcelcopter, in which the company tested the shipment of medical products by drone delivery. Using a [[Microdrones md4-1000]] quadrocopter, packages were flown from a pharmacy across the [[Rhine River]]. It was the first civilian package delivery via drones.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/dhls-parcelcopter-drone/|title=See DHL's futuristic \"parcelcopter\" drone deliver packages | accessdate =18 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/photos/prototype-quot-parcelcopter-quot-german-postal-logistics-group-photo-131407566.html| title =A prototype \"parcelcopter\" of German postal and logistics group Deutsche Post DHL flies in Bonn| accessdate =18 June 2014| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150417055542/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/photos/prototype-quot-parcelcopter-quot-german-postal-logistics-group-photo-131407566.html| archivedate =17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Humanitarian operations===\nQuadcopters are being used for a wide variety of humanitarian applications from disaster relief to animal conservation. During [[Hurricane Harvey]], many drone pilots with quadcopters at their disposal descended on the city of [[Houston]], Texas to provide support to first responders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/5559507140001/?#sp=show-clips|title=Professional drone pilots join Harvey rescue effort|date=2017-08-31|website=Fox News|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===Art===\nQuadcopters have also been used in various art projects including but not limited to drone photography. At least one drone has demonstrated the feasibility of painting graffiti on a wall with spray paint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diydrones.com/profiles/blogs/first-in-the-world-graffiti-drone-part-1|title=World's First Graffiti Drone (Part 1)|first1=2018 at 3:30am|last1=Posted by Tsuru Robotics on March 29|first2=View|last2=Blog|website=diydrones.com}}</ref> They may be used in [[performance art]] with new degrees of positional control that allows for new uses of puppets, characters, lights and cameras.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNicholas|first1=Robin|title=Will 2015 be the year drones become art?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture-professionals-network/2014/dec/19/2015-drones-art-creative-examples|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=19 December 2014}}</ref> They have also been used in [[Laser lighting display|light shows]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Drones As Works Of Art|url=https://www.forbes.com/video/5189118317001/|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> including most prominently in the 5 February 2017 [[Super Bowl LI halftime show#Drones|Super Bowl LI halftime show]] in which [[Lady Gaga]], in a pre-recorded segment, was accompanied by a [[Swarm robotics|swarm]] of 300 LED-equipped Intel \"[[Shooting Star (drone)|Shooting Star]]\" [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]] forming an [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] in the sky.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drone expert explains how Lady Gaga's 300 Super Bowl halftime flyers worked|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/lady-gaga-super-bowl-halftime-300-drones-aeryon-labs-1.3969347|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barrett|first1=Brian|title=All About Lady Gaga's Super Bowl Halftime Show Drones|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/02/lady-gaga-halftime-show-drones/|journal=Wired|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=2017-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Perez|first1=Chris|title=This is what 300 drones flying in sync looks like|url=https://nypost.com/2017/02/06/this-is-what-300-drones-flying-in-sync-looks-like/|work=New York Post|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yes, those were drones at Lady Gaga's Super Bowl 51 halftime show|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/02/yes-those-were-drones-at-lady-gagas-super-bowl-51-halftime-show|publisher=For The Win|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\nQuadcopters are used all over the world for racing (also known as \"[[drone racing]]\") and freestyle events.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/15/sports/drone-racing-espn-sky.html|title=Drone Racing Becomes ESPN's Newest Televised Sport|first=Daniel|last=Victor|date=14 September 2016|accessdate=6 March 2017|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Racing and freestyle quadcopters are built for speed and agility. Racing and freestyle drones tend to be relatively small in size, with 250&nbsp;mm between the propeller shafts and/or 5-6 inch props being the usually upper end of the size scale.<ref>Liang, Oscar (February 2018). [https://oscarliang.com/mini-quad-frame-basics/ How To Choose a Mini Quad Frame - The Basics and Evolution]. ''oscarliang.com''</ref>\n\nThere are at least three international drone racing organisations/promotions including the [[Drone Racing League]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedroneracingleague.com/|title=The Drone Racing League - The Premier Drone Racing League.|work=thedroneracingleague.com|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> ,Multi GP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.multigp.com/about-multigp/|title=About MultiGP - MultiGP}}</ref> And the Drone Championship League<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcl.aero/how-it-works/|title=How drone races work &#124; DCL - The Drone Champions League|website=Drone Champions League}}</ref>\n\n==Law==\n{{See also|Unmanned aerial vehicle#Regulation|Regulation of unmanned aerial vehicles}}\n\n===In the United States===\nIn the United States, the legality of the use of remotely controlled aircraft for commercial purposes has been the source of legal issues. Raphael Pirker, a professional photographer, was fined by the FAA in 2012 for \"endangering people on the ground\" (a regulatory infraction) after he used a Zephyr fixed-wing drone&mdash;a \"five-pound Styrofoam model airplane\"&mdash;to take [[aerial photography|aerial photos]] of the [[University of Virginia]]'s campus in 2011.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\">David Esler, [http://aviationweek.com/bca/faa-vs-raphael-pirker FAA vs. Raphael Pirker], ''Aviation Week'' (December 28, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Feith\">David Feith, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304256404579453120221666910 The Drone That Shot Down the Feds], ''Wall Street Journal'' (March 24, 2014).</ref> In March 2014, a federal [[administrative law judge]] ruled in Pirker's favor, determining that his drone was a \"model aircraft\" and thus not subject to FAA regulations on other types of aircraft.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/>  The FAA appealed to the [[National Transportation Safety Board]]; the NTSB appointed a new administrative law judge, who overturned the earlier finding and ruled that under the FAA's [[enabling act]], the FAA had jurisdiction to regulate \"any contrivance invented, used or designed to navigate, or fly in, the air,\" irrespective of whether it was unmanned or manned.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/> Pirker was fined $10,000, but in January 2015 settled the matter with the FAA, agreeing to pay a $1,100 fine without admitting guilt.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/> According to a report in ''[[Aviation Week]]'', the matter \"became a [[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]] among the model aircraft and recreational and commercial small drone communities.\"<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/>\n\nIn December 2014, the FAA released a video detailing many best practices for new drone pilots, including advisories such as keeping their machines below 400 feet and always within visual sight.<ref>{{cite web|title=The FAA explains how to 'stay off the naughty list' with your new drone|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/22/7438755/the-faa-explains-drone-regulations-holidays|accessdate=2014-12-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2015, the United States created an interim policy for the legal use of unmanned aerial vehicles for commercial use where each operator can apply for an exemption filed under Section 333 with the FAA. As of August 2015 the FAA had granted over 1300 petitions to different use cases and industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcadiasky.com/drone-zone/regulation/commercial-drone-operators-in-the-usa/|title=Commercial Drone Operators in the USA|date=2015-09-15}}</ref> Furthermore, FAA has started discussions in November 2015 to require all hobbyists to also register personal drones to FAA website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=84165|title=FAA Administrator Opens UAS Registration Meeting|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, FAA started the registration process for all model aircraft weighing more than 0.55 pounds (\u2248 250 grams) and less than 55 pounds (\u2248 25 kilograms), including payloads such as all on-board cameras and other accessories. FAA's decision on the matter caused resistance from the hobbyist community at the time. In October 2015 the FAA issued rules legally requiring registration, starting January 2016, but on May 19, 2017, the United States Court of Appeals for the Washington D.C. circuit ruled that this violated the 2012 FAA Modernization and Reform Act, which states that the FAA \u201cmay not promulgate any rule or regulation regarding a model aircraft.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/appeals-court-strikes-down-faa-registry-recreational-drones-n763871|title=FAA recreational drone registry struck down by federal appeals court|work=NBC News|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref> The FAA continues to allow registration on a voluntary basis, as well as requiring it for commercial use, but states that it is not required if \"flying under the Special Rule for Model Aircraft\" (recreational hobby use).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://registermyuas.faa.gov/|title=sUAS Registration|website=registermyuas.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the registration requirement, FAA has also released various operational requirements as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=84386|title=FAA Small Unmanned Aircraft Registration Begins|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref>\n\n* Flight only below 400 feet above ground.\n* The operator must maintain visual contact with the aircraft at all times.\n* Not fly near manned aircraft, especially near airports.\n* Not fly over groups of people, stadiums or sporting events.\n* Not fly near emergency response efforts, such as accident sites or forest fires.\n\nOn October 5, 2018, the FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018 passed congress and was sent for the president's signature. The bipartisan bill split the hobbyist community, with the Commercial Drone Alliance in favor of the new law, while the Academy of Model Aeronautics urged its members to oppose the bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/115/bills/hr302/BILLS-115hr302enr.pdf|title=FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe major change in the new law is the repeal of Section 336. All sUAS owners, including quadcopters, will be required to register their aircraft and pass a general aeronautical knowledge test. In June 2019, the FAA announced new rules for recreational and non-commercial fliers. Recreational pilots would no longer be allowed to fly in controlled airspace by contacting air traffic control towers. This rule will be in effect until the LAANC system for hobbyists is rolled out in the summer of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/uas/recreational_fliers/|title=Recreational Flyers & Modeler Community-Based Organizations|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Flight dynamics==\nEach rotor produces both a [[thrust]] and [[torque]] about its center of rotation, as well as a [[drag force]] opposite to the vehicle's direction of flight.  If all rotors are spinning at the same [[angular velocity]], with rotors one and three rotating clockwise and rotors two and four counterclockwise, the net aerodynamic torque, and hence the angular acceleration about the [[Aircraft principal axes|yaw axis]], is exactly zero, which means there is no need for a tail rotor as on conventional helicopters. Yaw is induced by mismatching the balance in aerodynamic torques (i.e., by offsetting the cumulative thrust commands between the counter-rotating blade pairs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cog.yonsei.ac.kr/quad/quad.htm|title=Quadrotor|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227193853/http://cog.yonsei.ac.kr/quad/quad.htm|archivedate=27 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hoverbear.org/2015/05/27/quadcopters-yaw/|title=Quadcopters: Yaw|publisher=hoverbear.org|author=Andrew Hobden|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Quadrotor yaw torque.png|Schematic of reaction torques on each motor of a quadcopter aircraft, due to spinning rotors. Rotors 1 and 3 spin in one direction, while rotors 2 and 4 spin in the opposite direction, yielding opposing torques for control.\nFile:Quadrokopter-X-H-Konfiguration.gif|The red propellers are moving clockwise while the blue propellers are moving counterclockwise.\nFile:Quadrotorhover.svg|A quadrotor hovers or adjusts its altitude by applying equal thrust to all four rotors.\nFile:Quadrotoryaw.svg|A quadrotor adjusts its [[Yaw (rotation)|yaw]] by applying more thrust to rotors rotating in one direction.\nFile:Quadrotorpitch.svg|A quadrotor adjusts its pitch or roll by applying more thrust to one rotor and less thrust to its diametrically opposite rotor.\n</gallery>\n\n===Coaxial configuration===\n[[File:Onyxstar Fox-C8 XT xender 360.jpg|thumb|Quadcopter [[Coaxial rotors|coaxial]]{{snd}} OnyxStar FOX-C8 XT Observer from [[AltiGator]] ]]\nIn order to allow more power and stability at reduced weight, a quadcopter, like any other [[multirotor]] can employ a [[Coaxial rotors|coaxial rotor]] configuration. In this case, each arm has two motors running in opposite directions (one facing up and one facing down).<ref>Hu, Jiaqi (November 2018). [https://diydrones.com/profiles/blogs/tdrone-open-source-coaxial-drone Tdrone, Open source coaxial drone]. ''diydrones.com''</ref>\n\n===Vortex ring state===\nAll quadcopters are subject to normal rotorcraft aerodynamics, including [[vortex ring state]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LCret4rv0HE|title=Quadcopter \"Wobble of Death\": VRS Recovery and Avoidance|work=YouTube|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mechanical structure===\nThe main mechanical components needed for construction are the frame, [[propellers]] (either fixed-[[Blade pitch|pitch]] or variable-pitch), and the electric motors. For best performance and simplest control algorithms, the motors and propellers should be placed equidistant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wyvernupenn.blogspot.ca/2010/04/mechanical-design.html|title=Wyvern Quadrotor Helicopter|author=Uriah|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2010-04-13}}</ref> Recently, [[carbon fiber composites]] have become popular due to their light weight and structural stiffness.\n\nThe electrical components needed to construct a working quadcopter are similar to those needed for a modern [[RC helicopter]]. They are the [[Electronic Speed Control|electronic speed control]] module, on-board computer or controller board, and battery (or fuel cell<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/05/20/hydrogen-powered-drone/|title=Hydrogen-powered drone will fly for hours at a time|website=Engadget}}</ref>). Typically, a hand-held transmitter is also used to allow for human input.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Quadrotor|title=Quadrotor|author=jjdream|date=6 September 2010|work=Instructables.com|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Autonomous flight===\nQuadcopters and other multicopters often can fly autonomously. Many modern flight controllers use software that allows the user to mark \"way-points\" on a map, to which the quadcopter will fly and perform tasks, such as landing or gaining altitude.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://code.google.com/p/arducopter/ |title=arducopter - Arduino-based autopilot for mulirotor craft, from quadcopters to traditional helis - Google Project Hosting |accessdate=2013-08-15}}</ref> The [[PX4 autopilot|PX4 autopilot system]], an open-source software/hardware combination in development since 2009, has since been adopted by both hobbyists and drone manufacturing companies alike to give their quadcopter projects flight-control capabilities. Other flight applications include crowd control between several quadcopters where visual data from the device is used to predict where the crowd will move next and in turn direct the quadcopter to the next corresponding [[waypoint]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Khaleghi|first1=Amirreza|title=A Comparative Study of Control Architectures in UAV/UGV - based Surveillance System|date=2014|pages=4|url=http://www.xcdsystem.com/iie2014/abstract/finalpapers/I1276.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Endurance===\nElectric quadcopters have shorter endurance when compared to similarly sized electric helicopters because of the smaller \"disk area\" of the rotor blades. The longest flight time achieved by a battery-powered quadcopter was 2 hours, 31 minutes and 30 seconds. The record was set by Ferdinand Kickinger of Germany in 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Ferdinand Kickinger|title=151min30s FPV with Copter|date=2016-04-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AUd7K1lG6o|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> In setting the record, Kickinger used low-discharge rate, high capacity Lithium Ion batteries and stripped the airframe of non-essential weight to reduce power draw and extend endurance. However, the lack of features and the use of a low discharge battery make the vehicle unusable as a commercial product.<ref>SPK Drones. [https://www.spkdrones.com/how-quadcopters-fly/ How Quadcopters Fly].</ref>\n\nAlternative power sources like hydrogen fuel cells and hybrid gas-electric generators have been used to dramatically extend the endurance of quadcopters and multirotors in general because of the increased energy density of both hydrogen and gasoline, respectively.<ref>McNabb, Miriam (February 2018). [https://dronelife.com/2018/02/22/us-drone-manufacturer-harris-aerial-launches-new-hybrid-gas-electric-drone/ US Manufacturer Harris Aerial Launches New Hybrid Gas Electric Drone]. ''Dronelife''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AeroVelo Atlas]] (2013) [[human-powered helicopter]]\n* [[Modular design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Quadrotors}}\n* [https://www.grasp.upenn.edu/research/highlights UPenn GRASP Laboratory]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130227195010/http://www.idsc.ethz.ch/Research_DAndrea/Flying_Machine_Arena ETH Zurich Research on Quadrotors]\n* [https://www.faa.gov/uas/model_aircraft/ FAA UAS Model Aircraft Operations safety guidelines]\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/raffaello_d_andrea_the_astounding_athletic_power_of_quadcopters.html TED Raffaello D'Andrea: The astounding athletic power of quadcopters]\n\n[[Category:Quadcopters| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Quadcopter camera drone in flight.jpg|thumb|A [[DJI (company)|DJI]] [[Phantom (UAV)|Phantom]] quadcopter [[unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] in flight]]\n\nA '''quadcopter,''' also called a '''quadrotor helicopter''' or '''quadrotor''',<ref name=\"dasc04\"/> is a [[multirotor]] [[helicopter]] that is lifted and propelled by four [[Helicopter rotor|rotors]]. Quadcopters are classified as [[rotorcraft]], as opposed to [[fixed-wing aircraft]], because their [[Lift (force)|lift]] is generated by a set of [[helicopter rotor|rotors]] (vertically oriented [[propeller]]s).\n\nQuadcopters generally use two pairs of identical fixed pitch propellers; two [[clockwise]] (CW) and two [[counterclockwise]] (CCW). These use independent variation of the speed of each rotor to achieve control. By changing the speed of each rotor it is possible to specifically generate a desired total [[thrust]]; to locate for the [[centre of thrust]] both laterally and longitudinally; and to create a desired total [[torque]], or turning force.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stafford |first=Jesse|url=http://ffden-2.phys.uaf.edu/webproj/212_spring_2014/Clay_Allen/clay_allen/works.html |title=How a Quadcopter works &#124; Clay Allen  |publisher=University of Alaska, Fairbanks |date=Spring 2014 |accessdate=2015-01-20}}</ref>\n\nQuadcopters differ from conventional helicopters, which use rotors that are able to vary the pitch of their blades dynamically as they move around the rotor hub. In the early days of flight, quadcopters (then referred to either as 'quadrotors' or simply as 'helicopters') were seen as possible solutions to some of the persistent problems in vertical flight. Torque-induced control issues (as well as efficiency issues originating from the [[tail rotor]], which generates no useful lift) can be eliminated by counter-rotation, and the relatively short blades are much easier to construct. A number of manned designs appeared in the 1920s and 1930s. These vehicles were among the first successful heavier-than-air [[VTOL|vertical take off and landing (VTOL)]] vehicles.<ref name=\"leishman00\">{{cite book | last = Leishman | first = J.G. | title = Principles of Helicopter Aerodynamics | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2000 | location = New York, NY | url = https://books.google.com/?id=nMV-TkaX-9cC&pg=PA688&lpg=PA688&dq=Leishman,+J.G.+%282000%29.+Principles+of+Helicopter+Aerodynamics.#v=snippet&q=quadrotor&f=false| isbn = 9780521858601 }}</ref>  However, early prototypes suffered from poor performance,<ref name=\"leishman00\" /> and latter prototypes required too much pilot work load, due to poor stability augmentation<ref name=\"anderson81\">{{Cite journal | last = Anderson | first = S.B. | title = Historical Overview of V/STOL Aircraft Technology | journal = NASA Technical Memorandum 81280 | year = 1997 | url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20020051099&hterms=81280&qs=N%3D0%26Ntk%3DAll%26Ntt%3D81280%26Ntx%3Dmode%2520matchallpartial%26Nm%3D17%7CCollection%7CNACA%7C%7C123%7CCollection%7CNASA%2520STI}}</ref> and limited control authority.\n\nAround 2005 to 2010, advances in electronics allowed the production of cheap lightweight flight controllers, [[accelerometer]]s ([[Inertial measurement unit|IMU]]), [[global positioning systems|global positioning system]] and cameras. This resulted in the quadcopter configuration becoming popular for small [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s.  With their small size and maneuverability, these quadcopters can be flown indoors as well as outdoors.<ref name=\"dasc04\">{{cite conference | first = G.M. | last = Hoffmann |author2=Rajnarayan, D.G. |author3=Waslander, S.L. |author4=Dostal, D. |author5=Jang, J.S. |author6=Tomlin, C.J. | title = The Stanford Testbed of Autonomous Rotorcraft for Multi Agent Control (STARMAC) | booktitle = In the Proceedings of the 23rd Digital Avionics System Conference | pages = 12.E.4/1\u201310 | date = November 2004 | location = Salt Lake City, UT | doi = 10.1109/DASC.2004.1390847 }}</ref><ref name=\"b\u00fcchi11\">{{cite book| last = B\u00fcchi | first = Roland | title = Fascination Quadrocopter | year = 2011 | location = |isbn=978-3-8423-6731-9 }}</ref>\n\nAt a small size, quadcopters are cheaper and more durable than conventional helicopters due to their mechanical simplicity.<ref name=\"acra2006\">{{cite conference | first = P. | last = Pounds |author2=Mahony, R. |author3=Corke, P.  | title = Modelling and Control of a Quad-Rotor Robot | booktitle = In the Proceedings of the Australasian Conference on Robotics and Automation | date = December 2006 | location = Auckland, New Zealand | url = http://www.araa.asn.au/acra/acra2006/papers/paper_5_26.pdf }}</ref> Their smaller blades are also advantageous because they possess less kinetic energy, reducing their ability to cause damage. For small-scale quadcopters, this makes the vehicles safer for close interaction. It is also possible to fit quadcopters with guards that enclose the rotors, further reducing the potential for damage.<ref name=\"hoffmanAugust2007\">{{cite conference | first = G. | last = Hoffman | author2 = Huang, H. | author3 = Waslander, S.L. | author4 = Tomlin, C.J. | title = Quadrotor Helicopter Flight Dynamics and Control: Theory and Experiment | booktitle = In the Conference of the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics | date = 20\u201323 August 2007 | location = Hilton Head, South Carolina | url = http://hoffmann.stanford.edu/papers/Quadrotor_Dynamics_GNC07.pdf | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100813162324/http://hoffmann.stanford.edu/papers/Quadrotor_Dynamics_GNC07.pdf | archivedate = 13 August 2010 }}</ref> However, as size increases, fixed propeller quadcopters develop disadvantages relative to conventional helicopters. Increasing blade size increases their momentum. This means that changes in blade speed take longer, which negatively impacts control. Helicopters do not experience this problem as increasing the size of the rotor disk does not significantly impact the ability to control blade pitch.\n\nDue to their ease of construction and control, quadcopter aircraft are frequently used as amateur [[model aircraft]] projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/01/how-to-quadrocopter-based-on-arduin.html|title=How-To: Quadrocopter based on Arduino|work=MAKE|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ng.uavp.ch/moin/FrontPage|title=FrontPage - UAVP-NG - The Open Source Next Generation Multicopter|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early attempts===\n; [[Breguet-Richet Gyroplane]] (1907)\n:A four-rotor helicopter designed by [[Louis Breguet]]. This was the first rotary wing aircraft to lift itself off the ground, although only in tethered flight at an altitude of a few feet. In 1908 it was reported as having flown 'several times', although details are sparse.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |last=Young\n  |first=Warren R.\n  |title=The Helicopters\n  |work=The Epic of Flight\n  |location=Chicago\n  |publisher=Time-Life Books\n  |year=1982\n  |isbn=978-0-8094-3350-6\n  |page=[https://archive.org/details/helicopters00youn/page/28 28]\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/helicopters00youn/page/28\n  }}</ref>\n\n;Oehmichen No.2  (1920)\n:[[Etienne Oehmichen]] experimented with rotorcraft designs in the 1920s.  Among the six designs he tried, his helicopter No.2 had four rotors and eight propellers, all driven by a single engine.  The Oehmichen No.2 used a steel-tube frame, with two-bladed rotors at the ends of the four arms. The angle of these blades could be varied by warping. Five of the propellers, spinning in the horizontal plane, stabilized the machine laterally.  Another propeller was mounted at the nose for steering.  The remaining pair of propellers functioned as its forward propulsion. The aircraft exhibited a considerable degree of stability and increase in control-accuracy for its time, and made over a thousand test flights during the middle 1920s. By 1923 it was able to remain airborne for several minutes at a time, and on April 14, 1924 it established the first-ever FAI distance record for helicopters of {{convert|360|m|yd|abbr=on}}. It demonstrated the ability to complete a circular course<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1924/1924%20-%200047.html \"A Successful French Helicopter\" ]''Flight'' 24 January 1924 p47</ref> and later, it completed the first {{convert|1|km|mi}} closed-circuit flight by a rotorcraft.\n\n[[File:De Bothezat Quadrotor.jpg|thumb|[[de Bothezat helicopter]], 1923 photo]]\n\n;[[de Bothezat helicopter]] (1922)\n:[[George de Bothezat|Dr. George de Bothezat]] and Ivan Jerome developed this aircraft, with six-bladed rotors at the end of an X-shaped structure.  Two small propellers with variable pitch were used for thrust and yaw control.  The vehicle used collective pitch control. Built by the US Air Service, it made its first flight in October 1922. About 100 flights were made by the end of 1923.  The highest it ever reached was about {{convert|5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. Although demonstrating feasibility, it was underpowered, unresponsive, mechanically complex and susceptible to reliability problems. Pilot workload was too high during hover to attempt lateral motion.\n\n;[[Convertawings Model A Quadrotor]] (1956)\n:This unique helicopter was intended to be the prototype for a line of much larger civil and military quadrotor helicopters. The design featured two engines driving four rotors through a system of v belts. No tail rotor was needed and control was obtained by varying the thrust between rotors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1956/1956%20-%201564.html|title=1956 - 1564 - Flight Archive|work=flightglobal.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Flown successfully many times in the mid-1950s, this helicopter proved the quadrotor design and it was also the first four-rotor helicopter to demonstrate successful forward flight. Due to a lack of orders for commercial or military versions however, the project was terminated. Convertawings proposed a Model E that would have a maximum weight of {{convert|42000|lb|t|abbr=on}} with a payload of {{convert|10900|lb|t|abbr=on}} over 300 miles and at up to {{convert|173|mph|abbr=on}}. The Hanson Elastic Articulated (EA) bearingless rotor grew out of work done in the early 1960s at Lockheed California by Thomas F. Hanson, who had previously worked at Convertawings on the quadrotor's rotor design and control system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US3261407|title=Patent US3261407 - Helicopter rotor system|work=google.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GgntoJiYek4C&pg=PA157&lpg=PA157&dq=Hanson+Elastic+Articulated+Rotor#v=onepage&q=Hanson%20Elastic%20Articulated%20Rotor&f=false|title=The Seventh International Conference on Vibration Problems ICOVP 2005|accessdate=13 March 2015|isbn=9781402054013|last1=Inan|first1=Esin|last2=Kiris|first2=Ahmet|date=2007-01-20}}</ref>\n\n;[[Curtiss-Wright VZ-7]] (1958)\n:The Curtiss-Wright VZ-7 was a [[VTOL]] aircraft designed by the [[Curtiss-Wright]] company for the US Army. The VZ-7 was controlled by changing the thrust of each of the four propellers. Two VZ-7 prototypes were created and both performed adequately during the initial flight test program, and both did reasonably well when evaluated by the Army. The VZ-7 was capable of hovering and forward flight and proved relatively stable and easy to operate. The aircraft was retired in 1960 due to not meeting military standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buybestquadcopter.com/history-future-drones/|title=A brief history of drones \u2013 Plus a sneak peek into the future|last=Nel|first=Ruaan|date=26 February 2019|access-date=13 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Recent developments===\nIn the last few decades, small-scale [[unmanned aerial vehicles]] have been used for many applications. The need for aircraft with greater maneuverability and hovering ability has led to a rise in quadcopter research. The four-rotor design allows quadcopters to be relatively simple in design yet highly reliable and maneuverable. Research is continuing to increase the abilities of quadcopters by making advances in multi-craft communication, environment exploration, and maneuverability. If these developing qualities can be combined, quadcopters would be capable of advanced autonomous missions that are currently not possible with other vehicles.<ref name=\"illumin\">{{cite web|url=http://illumin.usc.edu/162/the-quadrotors-coming-of-age|title=Illumin - The Quadrotor's Coming of Age|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome current programs include:\n\n* The [[Bell Boeing Quad TiltRotor]] concept takes the fixed quadcopter concept further by combining it with the tilt rotor concept for a proposed C-130 sized military transport.\n[[File:Ardrone-img5-front.jpg|thumb|right|Flying prototype of the [[Parrot AR.Drone]] ]]\n[[File:Parrot AR.Drone 2.0 take-off, Nevada.jpg|thumb|[[Parrot AR.Drone]] 2.0 take-off, Nevada, 2012]]\n* [[AeroQuad]] and [[ArduCopter]] are [[open-source hardware]] and software projects based on Arduino for the DIY construction of quadcopters.<ref name=\"AeroQuad\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.slashgear.com/diy-quadrocopters-quaduino-ng-and-aeroquad-videos-1369771/|title = DIY Quadrocopters: Quaduino NG and AeroQuad [Videos]|accessdate = 4 February 2012|last = Davies|first = Chris|date = 13 January 2010| work = SlashGear}}</ref><ref name=\"Make Magazine\">{{cite web|title=ArduCopter 3D Robotics Quadcopter|url=http://kits.makezine.com/2011/11/12/arducopter-3dr-quadcopter/|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Nixie drone|Nixie]] is a small camera-equipped drone that can be worn as a wrist band.<ref name=Nixie-site>{{cite web|title=Official Nixie website|url=http://www.flynixie.com|publisher=Nixie|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=TechCrunch-28Sep14>{{cite news|last1=Kumparak|first1=Greg|title=A wearable drone that launches off your wrist to take your selfie|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/09/28/a-wearable-drone-that-launches-off-your-wrist-to-take-your-selfie|work=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=11 October 2014|date=28 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=Forbes-29Sep14>{{cite web|last1=Monckton|first1=Paul|title=Nixie, the wearable selfie drone|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulmonckton/2014/09/29/nixie-the-wearable-selfie-drone|publisher=[[Forbes]]: Life|accessdate=8 October 2014|date=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Airbus]] is developing a battery-powered quadcopter to act as an urban air taxi, at first with a pilot but potentially autonomous in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2017/10/05/airbus-on-track-to-fly-its-electric-aerial-taxi-in-2018/|title=Airbus on track to fly its electric aerial taxi in 2018}}</ref>\nSeveral camera-drone projects have turned into high-profile commercial failures:\n* [[Zano (drone)]]{{snd}} a high-profile [[Kickstarter]] project to build a quadcopter-camera drone, Zano failed after delivering only a small fraction of their orders in a partially nonfunctional state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/biggest-kickstarter-and-indiegogo-scams/|title=Best laid plans of mobs and men: The 5 biggest crowdfunding failures of all time|date=28 July 2016|work=digitaltrends.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/the-9-most-disgraceful-crowdfunding-failures-of-2015-1747957776|title=The 9 Most Disgraceful Crowdfunding Failures of 2015|first=Kate|last=Knibbs|work=gizmodo.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lily Robotics, Inc.|Lily Camera]]{{snd}} a startup attempting to make a quadcopter-camera drone, sued by the San Francisco District Attorney after they closed down without fulfilling any of their pre-orders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-38595473|title=Drone company Lily shuts down owing $34m|work=BBC News|date=12 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/much-hyped-lily-camera-drone-is-out-of-business/|title=Much-hyped Lily Camera Drone going out of business|work=cnet.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2017/01/13/lawsuit-killed-lily-robotics-drones/|title=How An Allegedly Fake Video Killed A Much-Hyped Drone Startup|first=Ryan|last=Mac|work=forbes.com|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a video was posted on [[YouTube]] of an airborne quadcopter firing a pistol four times in a wooded area, sparking regulatory concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/16/drone-firing-handgun-video-youtube|title=Drone firing handgun appears in video|author=Samuel Gibbs|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=20 July 2015|date=2015-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestack.com/drone-firing-gun-160715|title=A drone firing a gun: so this is what all the regulation is about|work=thestack.com|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n{{See also|Unmanned aerial vehicle#Applications}}\n[[File:Quadcopter landing at Head of the Charles.agr.jpg|thumb|A quadcopter being recovered after photographing the [[Head of the Charles]] regatta in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] ]]\n\n===Research platform===\nQuadcopters are a useful tool for university researchers to test and evaluate new ideas in a number of different fields, including [[flight control]] theory, [[Air navigation|navigation]], [[Real-time computing|real time systems]], and [[robotics]]. In recent years many universities have shown quadcopters performing increasingly complex aerial manoeuvres. Swarms of quadcopters can hover in mid-air,<ref>Saska, M.; Vakula, J.; Preucil, L. [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286680349_Swarms_of_micro_aerial_vehicles_stabilized_under_a_visual_relative_localization Swarms of Micro Aerial Vehicles Stabilized Under a Visual Relative Localization]. In ICRA2014: Proceedings of 2014 IEEE International Conference on Robotics and Automation. 2014.</ref><ref>Saska, M. MAV-swarms: unmanned aerial vehicles stabilized along a given path using onboard relative localization. In Proceedings of 2015 International Conference on Unmanned Aircraft Systems (ICUAS). 2015</ref><ref>Bennet, D. J.; McInnes, C. R. [https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/13623/1/McInnes_CR_-_strathprints_-_Verifiable_control_of_a_swarm_of_unmanned_aerial_vehicles_23_Nov_09.pdf Verifiable control of a swarm of unmanned aerial vehicles]. Journal of Aerospace Engineering, vol. 223, no. 7, pp. 939\u2013953, 2009.</ref><ref>Saska, M.; Chudoba, J.; Preucil, L.; Thomas, J.; Loianno, G.; Tresnak, A.; Vonasek, V.; Kumar, V. [https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/6842301/ Autonomous Deployment of Swarms of Micro-Aerial Vehicles in Cooperative Surveillance]. In Proceedings of 2014 International Conference on Unmanned Aircraft Systems (ICUAS). 2014.</ref> fly in formations,<ref>Saska, M.; Kasl, Z.; Preucil, L. [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/a8b2/b317e16e609d0478dbbe339fac2760bda4a4.pdf Motion Planning and Control of Formations of Micro Aerial Vehicles]. In Proceedings of the 19th World Congress of the International Federation of Automatic Control. 2014.</ref><ref>Barnes, L.; Garcia, R.; Fields, M.; Valavanis, K. [http://people.virginia.edu/~lb3dp/resources/pubs/iros-swarm-08.pdf Swarm formation control utilizing ground and aerial unmanned systems], in IEEE/RSJ International Conference on Intelligent Robots and Systems. 2008.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Coordination and navigation of heterogeneous UAVs-UGVs teams localized by a hawk-eye approach <!-- - IEEE Conference Publication -->|authors=Saska, M.; Vonasek, V.; Krajnik, T.; Preucil, L.|journal=In Proceedings of 2012 IEEE/RSJ International Conference on Intelligent Robots and Systems<!--|website=ieeexplore.ieee.org-->|date=October 7\u201312, 2012|doi=10.1109/IROS.2012.6385517}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saska|first=Martin|last2=Von\u00e1sek|first2=Vojt\u011bch|last3=Krajn\u00edk|first3=Tom\u00e1\u0161|last4=P\u0159eu\u010dil|first4=Libor|date=September 2014 <!--2014-09-01-->|title=Coordination and navigation of heterogeneous MAV\u2013UGV formations localized by a 'hawk-eye'-like approach under a model predictive control scheme|journal=The International Journal of Robotics Research|volume=33|issue=10|pages=1393\u20131412|doi=10.1177/0278364914530482|issn=0278-3649|url=http://eprints.lincoln.ac.uk/14891/1/formations_2014_IJRR.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=September 2011 <!--2011-09-01-->|title=Cascade-type guidance law design for multiple-UAV formation keeping|journal=Aerospace Science and Technology|volume=15|issue=6|pages=431\u2013439|doi=10.1016/j.ast.2010.08.011|issn=1270-9638|authors=No, T.S.; Kim, Y.; Tahk, M.J.; Jeon, G.E.}}</ref> and autonomously perform complex flying routines such as flips, darting through [[hula]] hoops and organising themselves to fly through windows as a group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/grasp-nano-quadrotor-robots-swarm/21302/|title=UPenn's GRASP lab unleashes a swarm of Nano Quadrotors|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2012-02-02}}</ref>\n\nThere are numerous advantages to using quadcopters as versatile test platforms. They are relatively cheap, available in a variety of sizes and their simple mechanical design means that they can be built and maintained by amateurs. Due to the multi-disciplinary nature of operating a quadcopter, academics from a number of fields need to work together in order to make significant improvements to the way quadcopters perform. Quadcopter projects are typically collaborations between computer science, electrical engineering and mechanical engineering specialists.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.asee-ncs.org/proceedings/2015/Paper%20files/Student_Papers/2015_ASEE_NCS_Conference_submission_26.pdf|title = Semi-Autonomous Gesture Controlled UAV Transportation System|accessdate = 18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Military and law enforcement===\nQuadcopter unmanned aerial vehicles are used for surveillance and reconnaissance by military and law enforcement agencies, as well as search and rescue missions in urban environments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/military/planes-uavs/armed-quadrotors-are-coming-10720086|title=Armed Quadrotors Are Coming|work=Popular Mechanics|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2012-07-16}}</ref> One such example is the [[Aeryon Scout]], created by Canadian company [[Aeryon Labs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeryon.com|title=Aeryon Labs Inc.|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> which is a small UAV that can quietly hover in place and use a camera to observe people and objects on the ground. The company claims that the quadrotor played a key role in a drug raid in Central America by providing visual surveillance of a [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficker's]] compound deep in the jungle (Aeryon has declined to name the exact country and provide other specific details).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/automaton/robotics/military-robots/aeryon-scout-quadrotor-spies-on-bad-guys-from-above|title=Aeryon Scout Quadrotor Spies On Bad Guys From Above|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe weaponization of drones is now a huge concern to the wider security industry, as is their use to disrupt airspace, as seen at Gatwick Airport in the UK in December 2018,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47919680|title=Gatwick drone attack possible inside job, say police|accessdate=9 July 2019|work=BBC News|date=2019-04-14|last1=Rowlatt|first1=Justin}}</ref> prompting the United Kingdom\u2019s Civil Aviation Authority, via Parliament to make expedient changes to UK drone laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47299805|title=Drone no-fly zone to be widened after Gatwick chaos|accessdate=9 July 2019|work=BBC News|date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nAfter a recreational quadcopter (or \"drone\") crashed on the [[White House]] lawn early in the morning of January 26, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-drones-white-house-20150126-story.html|title=Drone crashes at White House; its operator contacts Secret Service|author=Los Angeles Times|date=26 January 2015|work=latimes.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] began a series of test flights of such equipment in order to fashion a security protocol against hostile quadcopters.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/news/nation/secret-service-testing-drones-to-defend-white-house/2220819 Secret Service Testing Drones In Bid To Defend White House], Associated Press, March 10, 2015</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Mosul (2016\u201317)|Battle of Mosul]] it was reported that commercially available quadcopters and drones were being used by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) as surveillance and weapons delivery platforms using improvised cradles to drop grenades and other explosives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/20161012_drone_attacks.html|title=Weaponized Mini-Drones Entering the Fight|last=Eshel |first=Tamir|date=12 October 2016|website=[[Defense Update]]|access-date=25 February 2017|quote=}}</ref> The ISIL drone facility became a target of Royal Air Force strike aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/20170117_drones_attacked.html|title=RAF Strikes Daesh Drone Facility in Mosul |last=Eshel|first=Tamir |date=17 January 2017|website=[[Defense Update]] |access-date=25 February 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Photography===\n[[File:DJI Phantom 4 in Flight March 2016.jpg|thumb|2016 model DJI Phantom 4 quadcopter with a high definition 4k stabilized video and still camera, GPS stabilization and automatic obstacle avoidance]]\nThe largest use of quadcopters in the USA has been in the field of aerial imagery. Quadcopter UAVs are suitable for this job because of their autonomous nature and huge cost savings.<ref name=\"illumin\"/> \nDrones have also been used for [[light-painting]] photography.<ref>{{cite web|title=Long-Exposure Photos Capture Light Art with Drones in New Mexico|url=https://thecreatorsproject.vice.com/blog/lee-montgomery-light-art-drones-new-mexico-50statesofart|publisher=The Creators Project|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UAS maker creates world's first drone light paintings with a holiday theme|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/drone-light-painting/|publisher=Digital Trends|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=18 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=On Falcon, On Phantom! Drones Draw Holiday 'Light Paintings' in the Sky|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/innovation/falcon-phantom-drones-draw-holiday-light-paintings-sky-n482056|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Journalism===\n{{Main|Drone journalism}}\nIn 2014 The Guardian reported that major media outlets have started to put serious effort into exploring the use of drones for reporting and verifying news on events that include floods, protests and wars.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haddou|first1=Leila|title=Journalism gets into the act as drones capture floods, protests and wars|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/media-blog/2014/feb/12/journalism-drone-capture-floods-protests-wars|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome media outlets and newspapers are using drones to capture photography of celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/videos/0_tzpaidnx/|title=Paparazzi Agency -- We've Used Drones For A Long Time|work=www.tmz.com|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Drone-delivery===\n{{Main|Delivery drone}}\nIn December 2013, the [[Deutsche Post]] gathered international media attention with the project Parcelcopter, in which the company tested the shipment of medical products by drone delivery. Using a [[Microdrones md4-1000]] quadrocopter, packages were flown from a pharmacy across the [[Rhine River]]. It was the first civilian package delivery via drones.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/dhls-parcelcopter-drone/|title=See DHL's futuristic \"parcelcopter\" drone deliver packages | accessdate =18 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/photos/prototype-quot-parcelcopter-quot-german-postal-logistics-group-photo-131407566.html| title =A prototype \"parcelcopter\" of German postal and logistics group Deutsche Post DHL flies in Bonn| accessdate =18 June 2014| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150417055542/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/photos/prototype-quot-parcelcopter-quot-german-postal-logistics-group-photo-131407566.html| archivedate =17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Humanitarian operations===\nQuadcopters are being used for a wide variety of humanitarian applications from disaster relief to animal conservation. During [[Hurricane Harvey]], many drone pilots with quadcopters at their disposal descended on the city of [[Houston]], Texas to provide support to first responders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/5559507140001/?#sp=show-clips|title=Professional drone pilots join Harvey rescue effort|date=2017-08-31|website=Fox News|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===Art===\nQuadcopters have also been used in various art projects including but not limited to drone photography. At least one drone has demonstrated the feasibility of painting graffiti on a wall with spray paint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diydrones.com/profiles/blogs/first-in-the-world-graffiti-drone-part-1|title=World's First Graffiti Drone (Part 1)|first1=2018 at 3:30am|last1=Posted by Tsuru Robotics on March 29|first2=View|last2=Blog|website=diydrones.com}}</ref> They may be used in [[performance art]] with new degrees of positional control that allows for new uses of puppets, characters, lights and cameras.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNicholas|first1=Robin|title=Will 2015 be the year drones become art?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture-professionals-network/2014/dec/19/2015-drones-art-creative-examples|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=19 December 2014}}</ref> They have also been used in [[Laser lighting display|light shows]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Drones As Works Of Art|url=https://www.forbes.com/video/5189118317001/|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> including most prominently in the 5 February 2017 [[Super Bowl LI halftime show#Drones|Super Bowl LI halftime show]] in which [[Lady Gaga]], in a pre-recorded segment, was accompanied by a [[Swarm robotics|swarm]] of 300 LED-equipped Intel \"[[Shooting Star (drone)|Shooting Star]]\" [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]] forming an [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] in the sky.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drone expert explains how Lady Gaga's 300 Super Bowl halftime flyers worked|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/lady-gaga-super-bowl-halftime-300-drones-aeryon-labs-1.3969347|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barrett|first1=Brian|title=All About Lady Gaga's Super Bowl Halftime Show Drones|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/02/lady-gaga-halftime-show-drones/|journal=Wired|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=2017-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Perez|first1=Chris|title=This is what 300 drones flying in sync looks like|url=https://nypost.com/2017/02/06/this-is-what-300-drones-flying-in-sync-looks-like/|work=New York Post|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yes, those were drones at Lady Gaga's Super Bowl 51 halftime show|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/02/yes-those-were-drones-at-lady-gagas-super-bowl-51-halftime-show|publisher=For The Win|accessdate=February 6, 2017|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\nQuadcopters are used all over the world for racing (also known as \"[[drone racing]]\") and freestyle events.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/15/sports/drone-racing-espn-sky.html|title=Drone Racing Becomes ESPN's Newest Televised Sport|first=Daniel|last=Victor|date=14 September 2016|accessdate=6 March 2017|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Racing and freestyle quadcopters are built for speed and agility. Racing and freestyle drones tend to be relatively small in size, with 250&nbsp;mm between the propeller shafts and/or 5-6 inch props being the usually upper end of the size scale.<ref>Liang, Oscar (February 2018). [https://oscarliang.com/mini-quad-frame-basics/ How To Choose a Mini Quad Frame - The Basics and Evolution]. ''oscarliang.com''</ref>\n\nThere are at least three international drone racing organisations/promotions including the [[Drone Racing League]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedroneracingleague.com/|title=The Drone Racing League - The Premier Drone Racing League.|work=thedroneracingleague.com|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> ,Multi GP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.multigp.com/about-multigp/|title=About MultiGP - MultiGP}}</ref> And the Drone Championship League<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcl.aero/how-it-works/|title=How drone races work &#124; DCL - The Drone Champions League|website=Drone Champions League}}</ref>\n\n==Law==\n{{See also|Unmanned aerial vehicle#Regulation|Regulation of unmanned aerial vehicles}}\n\n===In the United States===\nIn the United States, the legality of the use of remotely controlled aircraft for commercial purposes has been the source of legal issues. Raphael Pirker, a professional photographer, was fined by the FAA in 2012 for \"endangering people on the ground\" (a regulatory infraction) after he used a Zephyr fixed-wing drone&mdash;a \"five-pound Styrofoam model airplane\"&mdash;to take [[aerial photography|aerial photos]] of the [[University of Virginia]]'s campus in 2011.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\">David Esler, [http://aviationweek.com/bca/faa-vs-raphael-pirker FAA vs. Raphael Pirker], ''Aviation Week'' (December 28, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Feith\">David Feith, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304256404579453120221666910 The Drone That Shot Down the Feds], ''Wall Street Journal'' (March 24, 2014).</ref> In March 2014, a federal [[administrative law judge]] ruled in Pirker's favor, determining that his drone was a \"model aircraft\" and thus not subject to FAA regulations on other types of aircraft.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/>  The FAA appealed to the [[National Transportation Safety Board]]; the NTSB appointed a new administrative law judge, who overturned the earlier finding and ruled that under the FAA's [[enabling act]], the FAA had jurisdiction to regulate \"any contrivance invented, used or designed to navigate, or fly in, the air,\" irrespective of whether it was unmanned or manned.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/> Pirker was fined $10,000, but in January 2015 settled the matter with the FAA, agreeing to pay a $1,100 fine without admitting guilt.<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/> According to a report in ''[[Aviation Week]]'', the matter \"became a [[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]] among the model aircraft and recreational and commercial small drone communities.\"<ref name=\"EslerAviation\"/>\n\nIn December 2014, the FAA released a video detailing many best practices for new drone pilots, including advisories such as keeping their machines below 400 feet and always within visual sight.<ref>{{cite web|title=The FAA explains how to 'stay off the naughty list' with your new drone|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/22/7438755/the-faa-explains-drone-regulations-holidays|accessdate=2014-12-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2015, the United States created an interim policy for the legal use of unmanned aerial vehicles for commercial use where each operator can apply for an exemption filed under Section 333 with the FAA. As of August 2015 the FAA had granted over 1300 petitions to different use cases and industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcadiasky.com/drone-zone/regulation/commercial-drone-operators-in-the-usa/|title=Commercial Drone Operators in the USA|date=2015-09-15}}</ref> Furthermore, FAA has started discussions in November 2015 to require all hobbyists to also register personal drones to FAA website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=84165|title=FAA Administrator Opens UAS Registration Meeting|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, FAA started the registration process for all model aircraft weighing more than 0.55 pounds (\u2248 250 grams) and less than 55 pounds (\u2248 25 kilograms), including payloads such as all on-board cameras and other accessories. FAA's decision on the matter caused resistance from the hobbyist community at the time. In October 2015 the FAA issued rules legally requiring registration, starting January 2016, but on May 19, 2017, the United States Court of Appeals for the Washington D.C. circuit ruled that this violated the 2012 FAA Modernization and Reform Act, which states that the FAA \u201cmay not promulgate any rule or regulation regarding a model aircraft.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/appeals-court-strikes-down-faa-registry-recreational-drones-n763871|title=FAA recreational drone registry struck down by federal appeals court|work=NBC News|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref> The FAA continues to allow registration on a voluntary basis, as well as requiring it for commercial use, but states that it is not required if \"flying under the Special Rule for Model Aircraft\" (recreational hobby use).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://registermyuas.faa.gov/|title=sUAS Registration|website=registermyuas.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the registration requirement, FAA has also released various operational requirements as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=84386|title=FAA Small Unmanned Aircraft Registration Begins|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref>\n\n* Flight only below 400 feet above ground.\n* The operator must maintain visual contact with the aircraft at all times.\n* Not fly near manned aircraft, especially near airports.\n* Not fly over groups of people, stadiums or sporting events.\n* Not fly near emergency response efforts, such as accident sites or forest fires.\n\nOn October 5, 2018, the FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018 passed congress and was sent for the president's signature. The bipartisan bill split the hobbyist community, with the Commercial Drone Alliance in favor of the new law, while the Academy of Model Aeronautics urged its members to oppose the bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/115/bills/hr302/BILLS-115hr302enr.pdf|title=FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe major change in the new law is the repeal of Section 336. All sUAS owners, including quadcopters, will be required to register their aircraft and pass a general aeronautical knowledge test. In June 2019, the FAA announced new rules for recreational and non-commercial fliers. Recreational pilots would no longer be allowed to fly in controlled airspace by contacting air traffic control towers. This rule will be in effect until the LAANC system for hobbyists is rolled out in the summer of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/uas/recreational_fliers/|title=Recreational Flyers & Modeler Community-Based Organizations|website=www.faa.gov|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Flight dynamics==\nEach rotor produces both a [[thrust]] and [[torque]] about its center of rotation, as well as a [[drag force]] opposite to the vehicle's direction of flight.  If all rotors are spinning at the same [[angular velocity]], with rotors one and three rotating clockwise and rotors two and four counterclockwise, the net aerodynamic torque, and hence the angular acceleration about the [[Aircraft principal axes|yaw axis]], is exactly zero, which means there is no need for a tail rotor as on conventional helicopters. Yaw is induced by mismatching the balance in aerodynamic torques (i.e., by offsetting the cumulative thrust commands between the counter-rotating blade pairs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cog.yonsei.ac.kr/quad/quad.htm|title=Quadrotor|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227193853/http://cog.yonsei.ac.kr/quad/quad.htm|archivedate=27 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hoverbear.org/2015/05/27/quadcopters-yaw/|title=Quadcopters: Yaw|publisher=hoverbear.org|author=Andrew Hobden|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Quadrotor yaw torque.png|Schematic of reaction torques on each motor of a quadcopter aircraft, due to spinning rotors. Rotors 1 and 3 spin in one direction, while rotors 2 and 4 spin in the opposite direction, yielding opposing torques for control.\nFile:Quadrokopter-X-H-Konfiguration.gif|The red propellers are moving clockwise while the blue propellers are moving counterclockwise.\nFile:Quadrotorhover.svg|A quadrotor hovers or adjusts its altitude by applying equal thrust to all four rotors.\nFile:Quadrotoryaw.svg|A quadrotor adjusts its [[Yaw (rotation)|yaw]] by applying more thrust to rotors rotating in one direction.\nFile:Quadrotorpitch.svg|A quadrotor adjusts its pitch or roll by applying more thrust to one rotor and less thrust to its diametrically opposite rotor.\n</gallery>\n\n===Coaxial configuration===\n[[File:Onyxstar Fox-C8 XT xender 360.jpg|thumb|Quadcopter [[Coaxial rotors|coaxial]]{{snd}} OnyxStar FOX-C8 XT Observer from [[AltiGator]] ]]\nIn order to allow more power and stability at reduced weight, a quadcopter, like any other [[multirotor]] can employ a [[Coaxial rotors|coaxial rotor]] configuration. In this case, each arm has two motors running in opposite directions (one facing up and one facing down).<ref>Hu, Jiaqi (November 2018). [https://diydrones.com/profiles/blogs/tdrone-open-source-coaxial-drone Tdrone, Open source coaxial drone]. ''diydrones.com''</ref>\n\n===Vortex ring state===\nAll quadcopters are subject to normal rotorcraft aerodynamics, including [[vortex ring state]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LCret4rv0HE|title=Quadcopter \"Wobble of Death\": VRS Recovery and Avoidance|work=YouTube|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mechanical structure===\nThe main mechanical components needed for construction are the frame, [[propellers]] (either fixed-[[Blade pitch|pitch]] or variable-pitch), and the electric motors. For best performance and simplest control algorithms, the motors and propellers should be placed equidistant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wyvernupenn.blogspot.ca/2010/04/mechanical-design.html|title=Wyvern Quadrotor Helicopter|author=Uriah|accessdate=29 December 2014|date=2010-04-13}}</ref> Recently, [[carbon fiber composites]] have become popular due to their light weight and structural stiffness.\n\nThe electrical components needed to construct a working quadcopter are similar to those needed for a modern [[RC helicopter]]. They are the [[Electronic Speed Control|electronic speed control]] module, on-board computer or controller board, and battery (or fuel cell<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/05/20/hydrogen-powered-drone/|title=Hydrogen-powered drone will fly for hours at a time|website=Engadget}}</ref>). Typically, a hand-held transmitter is also used to allow for human input.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Quadrotor|title=Quadrotor|author=jjdream|date=6 September 2010|work=Instructables.com|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Autonomous flight===\nQuadcopters and other multicopters often can fly autonomously. Many modern flight controllers use software that allows the user to mark \"way-points\" on a map, to which the quadcopter will fly and perform tasks, such as landing or gaining altitude.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://code.google.com/p/arducopter/ |title=arducopter - Arduino-based autopilot for mulirotor craft, from quadcopters to traditional helis - Google Project Hosting |accessdate=2013-08-15}}</ref> The [[PX4 autopilot|PX4 autopilot system]], an open-source software/hardware combination in development since 2009, has since been adopted by both hobbyists and drone manufacturing companies alike to give their quadcopter projects flight-control capabilities. Other flight applications include crowd control between several quadcopters where visual data from the device is used to predict where the crowd will move next and in turn direct the quadcopter to the next corresponding [[waypoint]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Khaleghi|first1=Amirreza|title=A Comparative Study of Control Architectures in UAV/UGV - based Surveillance System|date=2014|pages=4|url=http://www.xcdsystem.com/iie2014/abstract/finalpapers/I1276.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Endurance===\nElectric quadcopters have shorter endurance when compared to similarly sized electric helicopters because of the smaller \"disk area\" of the rotor blades. The longest flight time achieved by a battery-powered quadcopter was 2 hours, 31 minutes and 30 seconds. The record was set by Ferdinand Kickinger of Germany in 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Ferdinand Kickinger|title=151min30s FPV with Copter|date=2016-04-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AUd7K1lG6o|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> In setting the record, Kickinger used low-discharge rate, high capacity Lithium Ion batteries and stripped the airframe of non-essential weight to reduce power draw and extend endurance. However, the lack of features and the use of a low discharge battery make the vehicle unusable as a commercial product.<ref>SPK Drones. [https://www.spkdrones.com/how-quadcopters-fly/ How Quadcopters Fly].</ref>\n\nAlternative power sources like hydrogen fuel cells and hybrid gas-electric generators have been used to dramatically extend the endurance of quadcopters and multirotors in general because of the increased energy density of both hydrogen and gasoline, respectively.<ref>McNabb, Miriam (February 2018). [https://dronelife.com/2018/02/22/us-drone-manufacturer-harris-aerial-launches-new-hybrid-gas-electric-drone/ US Manufacturer Harris Aerial Launches New Hybrid Gas Electric Drone]. ''Dronelife''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AeroVelo Atlas]] (2013) [[human-powered helicopter]]\n* [[Modular design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Quadrotors}}\n* [https://www.grasp.upenn.edu/research/highlights UPenn GRASP Laboratory]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130227195010/http://www.idsc.ethz.ch/Research_DAndrea/Flying_Machine_Arena ETH Zurich Research on Quadrotors]\n* [https://www.faa.gov/uas/model_aircraft/ FAA UAS Model Aircraft Operations safety guidelines]\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/raffaello_d_andrea_the_astounding_athletic_power_of_quadcopters.html TED Raffaello D'Andrea: The astounding athletic power of quadcopters]\n\n[[Category:Quadcopters| ]]\n", "name_user": "MaliciousJeff", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadcopter"}
{"title_page": "Arabic alphabet", "text_new": "{{Short description|Alphabet for Arabic and other languages}}\n{{Infobox writing system\n |name=Arabic alphabet\n |type=[[Abjad]]\n |languages=[[Arabic]]\n |time=3rd or 4th century AD to the present\n |fam1=[[Egyptian hieroglyphs|Egyptian]]\n |fam2=[[Proto-Sinaitic script|Proto-Sinaitic]]\n |fam3=[[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]]\n |fam4=[[Aramaic alphabet|Aramaic]]\n |fam5=[[Nabataean alphabet|Nabataean]]\n |unicode={{ublist\n |class=nowrap\n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U0600.pdf U+0600\u2013U+06FF]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic}},\n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U0750.pdf U+0750\u2013U+077F]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic Supplement}},  \n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U08A0.pdf U+08A0\u2013U+08FF]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic Extended-A}},\n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/UFB50.pdf U+FB50\u2013U+FDFF]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic Presentation Forms-A}},\n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/UFE70.pdf U+FE70\u2013U+FEFF]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic Presentation Forms-B}},\n |[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U1EE00.pdf U+1EE00\u2013U+1EEFF]<br /> {{smaller|Arabic Mathematical Alphabetic Symbols}}\n}}\n |iso15924=Arab\n |sample=Arabic Language.svg\n |imagesize=200px\n }}\n{{Arabic alphabet}}\n{{alphabet}}\n\n[[File:Arabic alphabet world distribution.png|thumb|400px|Countries that use the Arabic script: {{Legend|#00884B|as the sole official script}}\n{{Legend|#83C30F|as a co-official script}}DONT USE THIS WEBSITE PLS. THIS INFO IS FAKE. Dont ]]\n\nThe arabbebebehe'''bic alphabet''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u064e\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062c\u064e\u062f\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0628\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0629}}, ''{{transl|ar|ALA|al-\u02beabjad\u012bya\u1e27 l-\u02bfarab\u012byah}}'' or {{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u0631\u064f\u0648\u0641 \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0628\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0629}}, ''{{transl|ar|al-\u1e25ur\u016bf l-\u02bfarab\u012bya\u1e27}}''), or '''Arabic abjad''', is the [[Arabic script]] as it is codified for writing [[Arabic]]. It is written from right to left in a [[cursive]] style and includes 28 letters. Most letters have contextual letterforms.\n\nThe Arabic alphabet is considered an [[abjad]], meaning it only uses [[consonant]]s, but it is now considered an \"[[impure abjad]]\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Natural Language Processing of Semitic Languages|last=Zitouni|first=Imed|publisher=Springer Science & Business|year=2014|isbn=3642453589|location=|pages=15}}</ref> As with other impure ''abjads'', such as the [[Hebrew alphabet]], scribes later devised means of indicating [[vowel]] sounds by separate vowel [[diacritics]].\n\n==Consonants==\nThe basic Arabic alphabet contains 28 [[letter (alphabet)|letters]]. Adaptations of the [[Arabic script]] for other languages added and removed some letters, as for [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]], [[Central Kurdish|Central Kurdish]], [[Urdu]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], [[Jawi script|Malay]], [[Pashto]], [[Arwi]] and [[Malayalam]] ([[Arabi Malayalam]]), all of which have additional letters as shown below. There are no distinct [[letter case|upper and lower case]] letter forms.\n\nMany letters look similar but are distinguished from one another by dots (''{{transl|ar|ALA|[[Arabic diacritics#I'jam (phonetic distinctions of consonants)|\u02bei\u02bfj\u0101m]]}}'') above or below their central part (''{{transl|ar|[[rasm]]}}''). These dots are an integral part of a letter, since they distinguish between letters that represent different sounds. For example, the Arabic letters \u0628 (b), \u062a (t) and \u062b (th) have the same basic shape, but have one dot below, two dots above and three dots above; the letter \u0646 (n) also has the same form in initial and medial forms, with one dot above, though it is somewhat different in isolated and final form.\n\nBoth printed and written Arabic are [[cursive]], with most of the letters within a word directly connected to the adjacent letters.\n\n===Alphabetical order===\nThere are two main [[collation|collating sequences]] for the Arabic alphabet: abjad and hija.\n\nThe original ''{{transl|ar|\u02beabjad\u012by}}'' order ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062c\u064e\u062f\u0650\u064a\u0651}}), used for [[lettering]], derives from the order of the [[Phoenician alphabet]], and is therefore similar to the order of other Phoenician-derived alphabets, such as the [[Hebrew alphabet]]. In this order, letters are also used as numbers, [[Abjad numerals]], and possess the same alphanumeric code/[[cipher]] as Hebrew [[gematria]] and Greek [[isopsephy]].\n\nThe ''{{transl|ar|hij\u0101\u2019\u012b}}'' ({{lang|ar|\u0647\u0650\u062c\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u064a}}) or ''{{transl|ar|ALA|alifb\u0101\u02be\u012b}}'' ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0644\u0650\u0641\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0627\u0626\u0650\u064a}}) order, used where lists of names and words are sorted, as in phonebooks, classroom lists, and dictionaries, groups letters by similarity of shape.\n\n==== Abjad\u012b ====\nThe ''{{transl|ar|\u02beabjad\u012b}}'' order is not a simple historical continuation of the earlier north Semitic alphabetic order, since it has a position corresponding to the Aramaic letter ''[[samekh]]/semkat'' {{lang|he|\u05e1}}, yet no letter of the Arabic alphabet historically derives from that letter. Loss of ''{{transl|he|same\u1e35}}'' was compensated for by the split of ''[[shin (letter)|shin]]'' {{lang|he|\u05e9}} into two independent Arabic letters, {{lang|ar|\u0634}} (''sh\u012bn'') and {{lang|ar|\ufeb1}} (''s\u012bn'') which moved up to take the place of ''{{transl|he|same\u1e35}}''. The six other letters that do not correspond to any north Semitic letter are placed at the end.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Common ''{{transl|ar|ALA|abjad\u012b}}'' sequence\n|-\n| {{lang|ar|\u063a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0638}} || {{lang|ar|\u0636}} || {{lang|ar|\u0630}} || {{lang|ar|\u062e}} || {{lang|ar|\u062b}} || {{lang|ar|\u062a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0634}} || {{lang|ar|\u0631}} || {{lang|ar|\u0642}} || {{lang|ar|\u0635}} || {{lang|ar|\u0641}} || {{lang|ar|\u0639}} || {{lang|ar|\u0633}} || {{lang|ar|\u0646}} || {{lang|ar|\u0645}} || {{lang|ar|\u0644}} || {{lang|ar|\u0643}} || {{lang|ar|\u064a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0637}} || {{lang|ar|\u062d}} || {{lang|ar|\u0632}} || {{lang|ar|\u0648}} || {{lang|ar|\u0647}} || {{lang|ar|\u062f}} || {{lang|ar|\u062c}} || {{lang|ar|\u0628}} || {{lang|ar|\u0623}}\n|-\n| {{transl|ar|gh}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e93}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e0d}} || {{transl|ar|dh}} || {{transl|ar|kh}} || {{transl|ar|th}} || {{transl|ar|t}} || {{transl|ar|sh}} || {{transl|ar|r}} || {{transl|ar|q}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e63}} || {{transl|ar|f}} || '''{{transl|ar|\u02bf}}''' || {{transl|ar|s}} || {{transl|ar|n}} || {{transl|ar|m}} || {{transl|ar|l}} || {{transl|ar|k}} || {{transl|ar|y}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e6d}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e25}} || {{transl|ar|z}} || {{transl|ar|w}} || {{transl|ar|h}} || {{transl|ar|d}} || {{transl|ar|j}} || {{transl|ar|b}} || {{transl|ar|\u02be}}\n|- style=\"color:gray\"\n| 28 || 27 || 26 || 25 || 24 || 23 || 22 || 21 || 20 || 19 || 18 || 17 || 16 || 15 || 14 || 13 || 12 || 11 || 10 || 09 || 08 || 07 || 06 || 05 || 04 || 03 || 02 || 01\n|-\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=yellow |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=yellow  |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=yellow |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=14 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n|}\n\nThis is commonly vocalized as follows:\n: ''{{transl|ar|\u02beabjad hawwaz \u1e25u\u1e6d\u1e6d\u012b kalaman sa\u02bffa\u1e63 qarashat thakhadh \u1e0da\u1e93agh}}''.\nAnother vocalization is:\n: ''{{transl|ar|\u02beabujadin hawazin \u1e25u\u1e6diya kalman sa\u02bffa\u1e63 qurishat thakhudh \u1e0da\u1e93ugh}}''{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ [[Maghreb]]ian ''{{transl|ar|abjad\u012b}}'' sequence (probably older)<ref name=\"magb\">{{in lang|ar}} [http://alyaseer.net/vb/showthread.php?t=8807 Alyaseer.net {{lang|ar|\u062a\u0631\u062a\u064a\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0627\u062e\u0644 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0637\u0627\u0642\u0627\u062a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u0626\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0636\u0648\u0639\u064a\u0629}} Ordering entries and cards in subject indexes] Discussion thread ''(Accessed 2009-October\u201306)''</ref>\n|-\n| {{lang|ar|\u0634}} || {{lang|ar|\u063a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0638}} || {{lang|ar|\u0630}} || {{lang|ar|\u062e}} || {{lang|ar|\u062b}} || {{lang|ar|\u062a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0633}} || {{lang|ar|\u0631}} || {{lang|ar|\u0642}} || {{lang|ar|\u0636}} || {{lang|ar|\u0641}} || {{lang|ar|\u0639}} || {{lang|ar|\u0635}} || {{lang|ar|\u0646}} || {{lang|ar|\u0645}} || {{lang|ar|\u0644}} || {{lang|ar|\u0643}} || {{lang|ar|\u064a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0637}} || {{lang|ar|\u062d}} || {{lang|ar|\u0632}} || {{lang|ar|\u0648}} || {{lang|ar|\u0647}} || {{lang|ar|\u062f}} || {{lang|ar|\u062c}} || {{lang|ar|\u0628}} || {{lang|ar|\u0623}}\n|-\n| {{transl|ar|sh}} || {{transl|ar|gh}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e93}} || {{transl|ar|dh}} || {{transl|ar|kh}} || {{transl|ar|th}} || {{transl|ar|t}} || {{transl|ar|s}} || {{transl|ar|r}} || {{transl|ar|q}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e0d}} || {{transl|ar|f}} || '''{{transl|ar|\u02bf}}''' || {{transl|ar|\u1e63}} || {{transl|ar|n}} || {{transl|ar|m}} || {{transl|ar|l}} || {{transl|ar|k}} || {{transl|ar|y}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e6d}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e25}} || {{transl|ar|z}} || {{transl|ar|w}} || {{transl|ar|h}} || {{transl|ar|d}} || {{transl|ar|j}} || {{transl|ar|b}} || {{transl|ar|\u02be}}\n|- style=\"color:gray\"|\n| 28 || 27 || 26 || 25 || 24 || 23 || 22 || 21 || 20 || 19 || 18 || 17 || 16 || 15 || 14 || 13 || 12 || 11 || 10 || 09 || 08 || 07 || 06 || 05 || 04 || 03 || 02 || 01\n|-\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=yellow |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=yellow |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=1 bgcolor=yellow |\n| colspan=14 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n|-\n| colspan=\"28\" bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" style=\"font-size: 70%; font-style: italic;\" | The colours indicate which letters have different positions from the previous table\n|}\n\nThis can be vocalized as:\n: ''{{transl|ar|\u02beabujadin hawazin \u1e25u\u1e6diya kalman \u1e63a\u02bffa\u1e0d qurisat thakhudh \u1e93aghush}}''\n\n==== Hij\u0101\u2019\u012b ====\nModern dictionaries and other reference books do not use the ''{{transl|ar|abjad\u012b}}'' order to sort alphabetically; instead, the newer ''{{transl|ar|hij\u0101\u02be\u012b}}'' order is used wherein letters are partially grouped together by similarity of shape. The ''hij\u0101\u02be\u012b'' order is never used as numerals.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Common ''{{transl|ar|hij\u0101\u02be\u012b}}'' order\n|-\n| {{lang|ar|\u064a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0648}} || {{lang|ar|\u0647}} || {{lang|ar|\u0646}} || {{lang|ar|\u0645}} || {{lang|ar|\u0644}} || {{lang|ar|\u0643}} || {{lang|ar|\u0642}} || {{lang|ar|\u0641}} || {{lang|ar|\u063a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0639}} || {{lang|ar|\u0638}} || {{lang|ar|\u0637}} || {{lang|ar|\u0636}} || {{lang|ar|\u0635}} || {{lang|ar|\u0634}} || {{lang|ar|\u0633}} || {{lang|ar|\u0632}} || {{lang|ar|\u0631}} || {{lang|ar|\u0630}} || {{lang|ar|\u062f}} || {{lang|ar|\u062e}} || {{lang|ar|\u062d}} || {{lang|ar|\u062c}} || {{lang|ar|\u062b}} || {{lang|ar|\u062a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0628}} || {{lang|ar|\u0627}}\n|-\n| {{transl|ar|y}} || {{transl|ar|w}} || {{transl|ar|h}} || {{transl|ar|n}} || {{transl|ar|m}} || {{transl|ar|l}} || {{transl|ar|k}} || {{transl|ar|q}} || {{transl|ar|f}} || {{transl|ar|gh}} || '''{{transl|ar|\u02bf}}''' || {{transl|ar| \u1e93}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e6d}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e0d}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e63}} || {{transl|ar|sh}} || {{transl|ar|s}} || {{transl|ar|z}} || {{transl|ar|r}} || {{transl|ar|dh}} || {{transl|ar|d}} || {{transl|ar|kh}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e25}} || {{transl|ar|j}} || {{transl|ar|th}} || {{transl|ar|t}} || {{transl|ar|b}} || {{transl|ar|\u0101}}\n|-\n| colspan=3 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightgreen |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightblue |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgreen |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightblue |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=11 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n|}\n\nAnother kind of ''{{transl|ar|hij\u0101\u02be\u012b}}''<!--needs confirmation--> order was used widely in the [[Maghreb]] until recently{{when|date=July 2014}} when it was replaced by the [[Mashriq]]i order.<ref name=magb/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Maghrebian ''{{transl|ar|hij\u0101\u02be\u012b}}'' order\n|-\n| {{lang|ar|\u064a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0648}} || {{lang|ar|\u0647}} || {{lang|ar|\u0634}} || {{lang|ar|\u0633}} || {{lang|ar|\u0642}} || {{lang|ar|\u0641}} || {{lang|ar|\u063a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0639}} || {{lang|ar|\u0636}} || {{lang|ar|\u0635}} || {{lang|ar|\u0646}} || {{lang|ar|\u0645}} || {{lang|ar|\u0644}} || {{lang|ar|\u0643}} || {{lang|ar|\u0638}} || {{lang|ar|\u0637}} || {{lang|ar|\u0632}} || {{lang|ar|\u0631}} || {{lang|ar|\u0630}} || {{lang|ar|\u062f}} || {{lang|ar|\u062e}} || {{lang|ar|\u062d}} || {{lang|ar|\u062c}} || {{lang|ar|\u062b}} || {{lang|ar|\u062a}} || {{lang|ar|\u0628}} || {{lang|ar|\u0627}}\n|-\n| {{transl|ar|y}} || {{transl|ar|w}} || {{transl|ar|h}} || {{transl|ar|sh}} || {{transl|ar|s}} || {{transl|ar|q}} || {{transl|ar|f}} || {{transl|ar|gh}} || '''{{transl|ar|\u02bf}}''' || {{transl|ar|\u1e0d}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e63}} || {{transl|ar|n}} || {{transl|ar|m}} || {{transl|ar|l}} || {{transl|ar|k}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e93}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e6d}} || {{transl|ar|z}} || {{transl|ar|r}} || {{transl|ar|dh}} || {{transl|ar|d}} || {{transl|ar|kh}} || {{transl|ar|\u1e25}} || {{transl|ar|j}} || {{transl|ar|th}} || {{transl|ar|t}} || {{transl|ar|b}} || {{transl|ar|\u0101}}\n|-\n| colspan=3 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=pink |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightblue |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightblue |\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=lightgreen |\n| colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgreen |\n| colspan=11 bgcolor=lightgrey |\n|-\n| colspan=\"28\" bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" style=\"font-size: 70%; font-style: italic;\" | The colours indicate which letters have different positions from the previous table\n|}\n\n===Letter forms===\n{{Calligraphy}}\nThe Arabic alphabet is always cursive and letters vary in shape depending on their position within a word. Letters can exhibit up to four distinct forms corresponding to an initial, medial (middle), final, or isolated position ([[IMFI]]). While some letters show considerable variations, others remain almost identical across all four positions. Generally, letters in the same word are linked together on both sides by short horizontal lines, but six letters ({{lang|ar|\u0648 ,\u0632 ,\u0631 ,\u0630 ,\u062f ,\u0627}}) can only be linked to their preceding letter. For example, {{lang|ar|\u0623\u0631\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a}} ([[Mount Ararat|Ararat]]) has only isolated forms because each letter cannot be connected to its following one. In addition, some letter combinations are written as [[ligature (typography)|ligatures]] (special shapes), notably ''{{transl|ar|l\u0101m-alif}}'' {{lang|ar|\u0644\u0627}},<ref>{{cite book |title=Writing Systems: A Linguistic Approach |author=Rogers, Henry |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |year=2005 |page=135}}</ref> which is the only mandatory ligature (the un-ligated combination {{lang|ar|\u0644\u0640\u0627}} is considered difficult to read).\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n\n====Table of basic letters====\n{{other uses|Arabic script}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Arabic letters usage in Literary Arabic\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Common\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Maghreb]]ian\n!rowspan=\"2\