{"title_page": "John McClintock (theologian)", "text_new": "{{Infobox clergy\n| name          = The Rev. John McClintock\n| image         = File:John McClintock theologian portrait.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1814|10|27}}\n| birth_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1870|03|04|1814|10|27}}\n| death_place   = Madison, New Jersey\n| church        = St. Paul's Methodist Episcopal Church, New York City<br> American Chapel in Paris\n| other_names   =\n| education     = A. B. 1835  University of Pennsylvania  <ref name=\"Drew theological seminary 1895\">{{cite book|title=Drew Theological Seminary Alumni Record,  1869-1895|year=1895|publisher=Wilbur Ketcham|location=New York|pages=19\u201320|url=http://search.ancestry.com}}</ref> <br/> A. M. 1835 University of Pennsylvania <br/> D. D. 1848 University of Pennsylvania <br/> LL.D. Rutgers University 1866\n| ordained      =\n| religion      = Methodist\n| writings      = ''A First Book in Latin'' (1846)<br> ''A First Book in Greek'' (1848) ''Sketches of Eminent Methodist Ministers'' (1854)<br> ''Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological, and Ecclesiastical Literature'' (1867-1882)\n| offices_held  = Professor of Mathematics at Dickinson College (1836\u20131840)<br> Professor of Ancient Classics at Dickinson College (1840\u20131848) <br>Editor of ''The Methodist Review'' (1848\u20131856)<br>President and Professor of Practical Theology in Drew Theological Seminary (1867\u20131870)\n| title         =\n| spouse        = Caroline Augusta Wakeman<br> Catharine W. Stevenson\n| children      = 4\n| parents       = John McClintock Sr.<br>Martha McMackin\n| signature     =\n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes     =\n}}\n\n'''John McClintock''' (October 27, 1814 \u2013 March 4, 1870), American Methodist Episcopal theologian and educationalist, was born in [[Philadelphia]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Biography==\nMcClintock matriculated at [[Wesleyan University]] in [[Middletown, Connecticut]]. Ill health, however, forced him to leave Wesleyan in his freshman year.<ref name=\"uknow.drew.edu\">https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/DrewHistory/John+McClintock</ref> Unable to return, he graduated subsequently from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1835, and was assistant professor of mathematics (1836\u20131837), professor of mathematics (1837\u20131840), and professor of Latin and Greek (1840\u20131848) in [[Dickinson College]], [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]]. He opposed the [[Mexican\u2013American War]], as well as [[slavery]], but did not consider himself an abolitionist. In 1847 McClintock was arrested on the charge of instigating a riot, which resulted in the rescue of several fugitive slaves; his trial, in which he was acquitted, attracted wide attention.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} The trial dealt with the issue of [[Personal liberty laws]] in the North and the fugitive slave crisis.\n\n\"When [[Stephen Olin|President Olin]] of Wesleyan died, the chair was offered to McClintock, but he preferred the call to the editorship of ''The Methodist Quarterly Review'' [after 1885 ''The Methodist Review''],{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} a post which he held with distinction for eight years\" from 1848 to 1856.<ref name=\"uknow.drew.edu\"/><ref>https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60F10FC3F55147B93CAA8178BD95F458584F9</ref> He declined the Presidency of [[Troy University]] in 1855.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_mcClintockJ.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229132303/http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_mcClintockJ.htm |archivedate=2012-02-29 }}</ref> From 1857 to 1860 McClintock was pastor of St Paul's (Methodist Episcopal) Church, New York City; from 1860 to 1864 he had charge of the American chapel in Paris, and there and in London did much to turn public opinion in favour of the Northern States.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn 1865 to 1866 he was chairman of the central committee for the celebration of the centenary of American [[Methodism]]. He retired from the regular ministry in 1865, but preached in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]], until the spring of 1867, and in that year, at the wish of its founder, [[Daniel Drew]], became the first president of the newly established [[Drew Theological Seminary]] at [[Madison, New Jersey]]{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} (later, [[Drew University]]), where he died. At Drew, McClintock also served as professor of practical theology from 1867 until his death in 1870.\n\nA great preacher, orator and teacher, and a remarkably versatile scholar, McClintock by his editorial and educational work probably did more than any other man to raise the intellectual tone of American Methodism, and, particularly, of the American Methodist clergy.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Works==\nHe introduced to his denomination the scholarly methods of the new German theology of the day\u2014not only by his translation (with [[Charles E. Blumenthal]]) of [[Johann August Wilhelm Neander|Neander]]'s ''Life of Christ'' (1847), and of [[F\u00e9lix Bungener]]'s ''History of the Council of Trent'' (1855), but by his great project, McClintock and Strong's ''Cyclopaedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature'' (10 vols., 1867\u20131881; ''Supplement'', 2 vols., 1885\u20131887), in the editing of which he was associated with [[James Strong (theologian)|Dr James Strong]] (1822\u20131894), professor of [[exegesis|exegetical]] theology in the [[Drew Theological Seminary]] from 1868 to 1893, and the sole supervising editor of the last six volumes of the ''Cyclopaedia'' and of the supplement.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nWith [[George Richard Crooks]] (1822\u20131897), his colleague at [[Dickinson College]] and in 1880\u20131897 professor of historical theology at Drew Seminary, McClintock edited several elementary textbooks in [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]] (of which some were republished in Spanish), based on the pedagogical principle of imitation and constant repetition.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nAmong McClintock's other publications are:\n* ''Sketches of Eminent Methodist Ministers'' (1863)\n* an edition of [[Richard Watson (Methodist)|Richard Watson]]'s ''Theological Institutes'' (1851)\n* ''The Life and Letters of Rev. Stephen Olin'' (1854).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n*{{Cite encyclopedia |language=en |ref=harv |language=en |last=Chisholm |first=Hugh |title=McClintock, John |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |volume=17 |date=1911 |pages=204 |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/McClintock,_John}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |language=en |last=Crooks |first=G. R. |title=Life and Letters of the Rev. Dr John McClintock |location=New York |publisher=Nelson & Philips |year=1876}}\n*{{Cite AmCyc |last=Worman |first=J. H. |wstitle=McClintock, John|short=x}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|107644564}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McClintock, John}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American theologians]]\n[[Category:American Methodist clergy]]\n[[Category:Arminian ministers]]\n[[Category:Arminian theologians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Green-Wood Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Clergy from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Dickinson College faculty]]\n[[Category:Drew University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the Methodist Episcopal Church]]\n[[Category:Methodist ministers]]\n[[Category:Methodist theologians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Drew University]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox clergy\n| name          = The Rev. John McClintock\n| image         = File:John McClintock theologian portrait.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1814|10|27}}\n| birth_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1870|03|04|1814|10|27}}\n| death_place   = Madison, New Jersey\n| church        = St. Paul's Methodist Episcopal Church, New York City<br> American Chapel in Paris\n| other_names   =\n| education     = A. B. 1835  University of Pennsylvania  <ref name=\"Drew theological seminary 1895\">{{cite book|title=Drew Theological Seminary Alumni Record,  1869-1895|year=1895|publisher=Wilbur Ketcham|location=New York|pages=19\u201320|url=http://search.ancestry.com}}</ref> <br/> A. M. 1835 University of Pennsylvania <br/> D. D. 1848 University of Pennsylvania <br/> LL.D. Rutgers University 1866\n| ordained      =\n| religion      = Methodist\n| writings      = ''A First Book in Latin'' (1846)<br> ''A First Book in Greek'' (1848) ''Sketches of Eminent Methodist Ministers'' (1854)<br> ''Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological, and Ecclesiastical Literature'' (1867-1882)\n| offices_held  = Professor of Mathematics at Dickinson College (1836\u20131840)<br> Professor of Ancient Classics at Dickinson College (1840\u20131848) <br>Editor of ''The Methodist Review'' (1848\u20131856)<br>President and Professor of Practical Theology in Drew Theological Seminary (1867\u20131870)\n| title         =\n| spouse        = Caroline Augusta Wakeman<br> Catharine W. Stevenson\n| children      = 4\n| parents       = John McClintock Sr.<br>Martha McMackin\n| signature     =\n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes     =\n}}\n'''John McClintock''' (October 27, 1814 \u2013 March 4, 1870), American Methodist Episcopal theologian and educationalist, was born in [[Philadelphia]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Biography==\nMcClintock matriculated at [[Wesleyan University]] in [[Middletown, Connecticut]]. Ill health, however, forced him to leave Wesleyan in his freshman year.<ref name=\"uknow.drew.edu\">https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/DrewHistory/John+McClintock</ref> Unable to return, he graduated subsequently from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1835, and was assistant professor of mathematics (1836\u20131837), professor of mathematics (1837\u20131840), and professor of Latin and Greek (1840\u20131848) in [[Dickinson College]], [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]]. He opposed the [[Mexican\u2013American War]], as well as [[slavery]], but did not consider himself an abolitionist. In 1847 McClintock was arrested on the charge of instigating a riot, which resulted in the rescue of several fugitive slaves; his trial, in which he was acquitted, attracted wide attention.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} The trial dealt with the issue of [[Personal liberty laws]] in the North and the fugitive slave crisis.\n\n\"When [[Stephen Olin|President Olin]] of Wesleyan died, the chair was offered to McClintock, but he preferred the call to the editorship of ''The Methodist Quarterly Review'' [after 1885 ''The Methodist Review''],{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} a post which he held with distinction for eight years\" from 1848 to 1856.<ref name=\"uknow.drew.edu\"/><ref>https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60F10FC3F55147B93CAA8178BD95F458584F9</ref> He declined the Presidency of [[Troy University]] in 1855.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_mcClintockJ.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229132303/http://chronicles.dickinson.edu/encyclo/m/ed_mcClintockJ.htm |archivedate=2012-02-29 }}</ref> From 1857 to 1860 McClintock was pastor of St Paul's (Methodist Episcopal) Church, New York City; from 1860 to 1864 he had charge of the American chapel in Paris, and there and in London did much to turn public opinion in favour of the Northern States.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn 1865 to 1866 he was chairman of the central committee for the celebration of the centenary of American [[Methodism]]. He retired from the regular ministry in 1865, but preached in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]], until the spring of 1867, and in that year, at the wish of its founder, [[Daniel Drew]], became the first president of the newly established [[Drew Theological Seminary]] at [[Madison, New Jersey]]{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} (later, [[Drew University]]), where he died. At Drew, McClintock also served as professor of practical theology from 1867 until his death in 1870.\n\nA great preacher, orator and teacher, and a remarkably versatile scholar, McClintock by his editorial and educational work probably did more than any other man to raise the intellectual tone of American Methodism, and, particularly, of the American Methodist clergy.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Works==\n\nHe introduced to his denomination the scholarly methods of the new German theology of the day\u2014not only by his translation (with [[Charles E. Blumenthal]]) of [[Johann August Wilhelm Neander|Neander]]'s ''Life of Christ'' (1847), and of [[F\u00e9lix Bungener]]'s ''History of the Council of Trent'' (1855), but by his great project, McClintock and Strong's ''Cyclopaedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature'' (10 vols., 1867\u20131881; ''Supplement'', 2 vols., 1885\u20131887), in the editing of which he was associated with [[James Strong (theologian)|Dr James Strong]] (1822\u20131894), professor of [[exegesis|exegetical]] theology in the [[Drew Theological Seminary]] from 1868 to 1893, and the sole supervising editor of the last six volumes of the ''Cyclopaedia'' and of the supplement.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nWith [[George Richard Crooks]] (1822\u20131897), his colleague at [[Dickinson College]] and in 1880\u20131897 professor of historical theology at Drew Seminary, McClintock edited several elementary textbooks in [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]] (of which some were republished in Spanish), based on the pedagogical principle of imitation and constant repetition.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nAmong McClintock's other publications are:\n* ''Sketches of Eminent Methodist Ministers'' (1863)\n* an edition of [[Richard Watson (Methodist)|Richard Watson]]'s ''Theological Institutes'' (1851)\n* ''The Life and Letters of Rev. Stephen Olin'' (1854).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n*{{Cite encyclopedia |language=en |ref=harv |language=en |last=Chisholm |first=Hugh |title=McClintock, John |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |volume=17 |date=1911 |pages=204 |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/McClintock,_John}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |language=en |last=Crooks |first=G. R. |title=Life and Letters of the Rev. Dr John McClintock |location=New York |publisher=Nelson & Philips |year=1876}}\n*{{Cite AmCyc |last=Worman |first=J. H. |wstitle=McClintock, John|short=x}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|107644564}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McClintock, John}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American theologians]]\n[[Category:American Methodist clergy]]\n[[Category:Arminian ministers]]\n[[Category:Arminian theologians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Green-Wood Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Clergy from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Dickinson College faculty]]\n[[Category:Drew University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the Methodist Episcopal Church]]\n[[Category:Methodist ministers]]\n[[Category:Methodist theologians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Drew University]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Telikalive", "label": "safe", "comment": "form", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McClintock_(theologian)"}
