 Channel 34<br />\n'''[[Nikk\u014d, Tochigi]]'''<br />Analog: Channel 54<br />\n'''[[Maebashi, Gunma]]'''<br />Analog: Channel 54<br />Digital: Channel 33<br />\n'''[[Kiry\u016b, Gunma]]'''<br />Analog: Channel 53<br />\n'''[[Numata, Gunma]]'''<br />Analog: Channel 53<br />\n'''[[Hiratsuka, Kanagawa]]'''<br />Analog: Channel 35<br />Digital: Channel 25\n| affiliations             = [[Nippon News Network]]\n| owner                    = Nippon Television Network Corporation\n| licensee                 = \n| founded                  = {{start date|1952|10|28}}\n| airdate                  = August 28, 1953\n| callsign_meaning         = \n| sister_stations          = '''BS Nittele'''<br />'''BS Nittele 4K'''<br />'''Nittele Plus'''<br />'''Nittele News 24'''<br />'''Nittele G+'''\n| callsigns                = \n| former_channel_numbers   = [[Analog television|Analog]]:<br />4 ch (VHF) (1953-2011) [[Digital television|Digital]]:<br />4 ch\n| former_affiliations      = \n| effective_radiated_power = 10 kW (68 kW [[Effective radiated power|ERP]])\n| HAAT                     = \n| class                    = \n| facility_id              = \n| coordinates              = {{coord|35|39|31|N|139|44|44|E|type:landmark_region:JP-13_scale:2000}}\n| homepage                 = [http://www.ntv.co.jp/ http://www.ntv.co.jp]\n| telephone                = \n}}\n'''JOAX-DTV''', branded as {{nihongo|'''Nippon TV'''|\u65e5\u672c\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3|Nihon Terebi}}, is the [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]] of the [[Nippon Television Network System]], [[owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] by the {{nihongo foot|'''Nippon Television Network Corporation'''|\u65e5\u672c\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u653e\u9001\u7db2\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Nippon Terebi H\u014ds\u014dm\u014d kabushiki gaisha|group=lower-alpha}} subsidiary of certified broadcasting holding company {{nihongo foot|'''Nippon Television Holdings, Inc.'''|\u65e5\u672c\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Nihon Terebi H\u014drudingusu kabushiki gaisha|group=lower-alpha}}, itself a [[public company|listed]] subdisiary of [[Yomiuri Shimbun#Yomiuri Group|The Yomiuri Shimbun Holdings]], Japan's largest media conglomerate; Nippon Television Holdings forms part of Yomiuri's main television broadcasting arm alongside [[Kansai region]] flagship [[Yomiuri Telecasting Corporation]], which owns a 6.4% share in the company.{{efn|Both The Yomiuri Shimbun Holdings and Nippon TV Holdings owns shares outstanding in all (if not all, nearly all) affiliate stations of NNS.}} Nippon TV's studios are located in the [[Shiodome]] area of [[Minato, Tokyo]], [[Japan]] and its transmitters are located in the [[Tokyo Skytree]]. Broadcasting terrestrially across Japan, the network is sometimes [[Japanese abbreviated and contracted words|contracted]] to {{nihongo||\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec|Nittere}}, and abbreviated as \"'''NTV'''\" or \"'''AX'''\".\n\n==History of Nippon Television==\nIn July 1952, Nippon TV was granted the first TV broadcasting license in Japan.<ref name=\"ntvhistory\"/> The Nippon Television Network Corporation was established in October of the same year.<ref name=\"ntv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.co.jp/english/an/index_01cd.html|title=Corporate Data: ABOUT Nippon TV\uff5c[http://www.9animes.com/ Nippon TV]|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> On August 28, 1953, Nippon Television signed on as Asia's first commercial TV station with an animated dove spreading its wings in the logo (similar to [[NBC]]'s peacock logo introduced three years later). Japan's first television commercial (for [[Seikosha]] clocks) also aired at the same time.<ref name=\"ntv\" />\n\nIn December 1958, NTV introduced [[videotape]] recording in a one-off drama series using American RCA 2-inch quad tape. In December 1959, NTV aired Japan's first color VTR broadcast ''[[The Perry Como Show|Perry Como\u2019s Kraft Music Hall]]'' from NBC (U.S.A.). On September 10, 1960, NTV was given the right to broadcast [[color television]].<ref name=\"ntvhistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.co.jp/english/an/index_05ch.html|title=Corporate History|website=Nippon TV|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> On November 22, 1963, using a communication satellite relay, NTV conducted the first black-and-white TV transmission experiment between Japan and the United States during coverage of the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy]].\n\n*April 1, 1966: [[Nippon News Network]] (NNN) is formed.\n*July 1, 1966: [[The Beatles]]\u2019 concert at the [[Nippon Budokan]], part of their Japanese tour, was shown in color on NTV (prerecorded on tape), with the viewing rate reaching 56 percent.\n*1967: NTV\u2019s [[New York City]] bureau is opened. Overseas news is broadcast via satellite relay from a special studio set up within NBC.\n*October 9, 1969: [[Matsutaro Shoriki]], the founder of NTV and Yomiuri Group, dies.\n*1972: [[Nippon Television Network System]] (NNS) is formed.\n*January 14, 1973: NTV airs the live satellite relay in Japan for [[Elvis: Aloha from Hawaii|Elvis Presley\u2019s show in Hawaii, U.S.A.]].\n*1973: NTV enters into an agreement with [[ABC News]] in the U.S. for newscasts and satellite relays.\n*1974: NTV's [[London]] News Bureau opens.\n*October 8 & 15, 1975: The classic film ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' makes its world television premiere on NTV (Part I on the 8th, Part II on the 15th), about 13 months before NBC airs the film in the North America.\n\n[[File:NTV Symbol 1978.svg|thumb|200px|''[[Mon (emblem)|Monsh\u014d]]'' of Nippon TV since 1978]]\n\n*March 5, 1979: ''Zoom! Morning!'' ([[jp:\u30ba\u30fc\u30e0\u30a4\u30f3!!\u671d!]]) airs for the first time.\n*December 1982: [[Multichannel television sound]] broadcasting begins.\n*1985: NTV completes its own television studio in New York City, which is later sold to [[CBS]].\n*October 1987: A recording of [[Michael Jackson]]\u2019s concert at [[Yokohama Stadium]] is broadcast in Japan.\n*1987: NTV's cable news channel, NCN, is launched.<ref name=\"ntvhistory\" />\n*August 24, 1989: Broadcasting in [[Enhanced-definition television|enhanced definition]] begins.\n*1989: Completion of the [[:ja:\u751f\u7530\u30b9\u30bf\u30b8\u30aa|Ikuta Studios]].\n*1993: [[Hayao Miyazaki]] of [[Studio Ghibli|Studio Ghibli, Inc.]] designs Nippon Television's mascot character {{nihongo|'''''[[Studio Ghibli short films#Nandar\u014d|Nandar\u014d]]'''''|\u306a\u3093\u3060\u308d\u3046||lit. ''What Is It?''}} to commemorate the channel's 40th Anniversary.<ref name=\"ntvhistory\" />\n*July 13, 1995: Broadcasting in widescreen EDTV begins.\n*April 1998 NCN relaunches as 24-hour news channel, NNN24, available via cable (within [[Japan]]) and satellite (in [[Japan]], [[South Korea|Korea]], and [[Taiwan]]).\n*July 2003: The internal network name changes (\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec, Nippon Television), however \"NTV\" is still used for overseas as the same font as \"\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\".\n*February 29, 2004: Nippon Television moves its headquarters from Kojimachi to [[Shiodome]]. Regular [[High-definition television|high-definition]] production begins.\n*2011: Nittele becomes the top broadcaster in Japan, beating the previous record-holder [[Fuji Television]].<ref name=\"oricon20120102\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/2005397/full/|script-title=ja:\u307f\u3093\u306a\u30df\u30bf\uff01\u3000\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\"\u30df\u30bf\u52b9\u679c\"\u30678\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u8996\u8074\u73873\u51a0\u738b|work=Oricon|accessdate=13 March 2012|date=2 January 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> NTV's victory was propelled by high ratings of its Wednesday nightly drama ''[[Kaseifu no Mita]]''.\n*April 26, 2012: Nippon Television Network Preparatory Corporation is founded. \n*October 1, 2012: Nippon Television Network Corporation (first) transitions to a certified broadcasting holding company, Nippon Television Holdings, Inc., and Nippon Television Network Preparatory Corporation is renamed Nippon Television Network Corporation (second).\n*February 1\u20132, 2013: NTV and [[NHK General TV]] (which is also celebrating its own 60th year) collaborate for a two-day TV special.\n*January 2014: English name is changed from Nippon Television to Nippon TV.\n*February 27, 2014: Nippon TV acquires [[Hulu]] service in Japan (HJ Holdings LLC).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/global/hulu-japan-to-be-acquired-by-nippon-tv-1201122915/|title=Hulu Japan to Be Acquired by Nippon TV|last=Spangler|first=Todd|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=27 February 2014|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.hulu.com/2014/02/27/an-international-update-from-hulu-in-japan/|title=An International Update From Hulu in Japan|last=Hopkins|first=Mike|website=[[Hulu]]|date=27 February 2014|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Publicity events==\nOn March 9, 1984, [[Dan Goodwin]], aka Spider Dan, Skyscraperman, in a paid publicity event, used suction cups to climb the 10 floor Nippon Television Kojimachi Annex in Chiyoda.<ref name=\"Skyscraper Defense\">{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperdefense.com/building_climbs.html|title=Skyscraper Defense|accessdate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural projects==\n1980s: The ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] in the [[Vatican City]] was cleaned with NTV's financial help.<ref name=\"NYT\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/06/arts/design/06lisa.html The New York Times 'In Louvre, New Room With View of 'Mona Lisa'']</ref> (see also: [[Restoration of the Sistine Chapel frescoes]])\n\nApril 2005: The [[Mona Lisa]] Viewing Room at the [[Louvre]], Paris, was completed. The renovation was sponsored by NTV.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nJuly 2010: The renovation of the exhibition area in the Louvre for [[Venus de Milo]] was also completed with the support of NTV.<ref>[http://www.louvre.fr/llv/mecenat/remerciements_entreprises.jsp?CONTENT%3C%3Ecnt_id=10134198674088241&CURRENT_LLV_FICHE%3C%3Ecnt_id=10134198674088241&FOLDER%3C%3Efolder_id=9852723696501601&bmLocale=en The Louvre]</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting==\n===Digital TV===\n*Call sign: '''JOAX-DTV'''\n*Remote controller ID 4\n*[[Tokyo Skytree]]: Channel 25\n*Mito: Channel 14\n*Utsunomiya: Channel 34\n*Maebashi: Channel 33\n*Hiratsuka: Channel 25\n\n===Analog TV===\nStopped analog TV on July 24, 2011.\n*Call sign: '''JOAX-TV'''\n*[[Tokyo Tower]]: Channel 4\n*Mito: Channel 42\n*Hitachi: Channel 54\n*Utsunomiya: Channel 53\n*Nikko: Channel 54\n*Maebashi: Channel 54\n*Kiryu: Channel 53\n*Numata: Channel 53\n*Hiratsuka: Channel 35\n\n==Network==\n*[[Yomiuri Telecasting Corporation|Yomiuri TV]], Analog Channel 10, Digital Channel 14 [ID: 10] - Headquartered in [[Osaka]], broadcast in the [[Kansai]] area\n*[[Chukyo TV. Broadcasting|Chukyo TV]], Analog Channel 35, Digital Channel 19 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Nagoya]], broadcast in the Chukyo area \n*[[Sapporo Television Broadcasting|Sapporo TV]], Analog Channel 5, Digital Channel 21 [ID: 5] - Headquartered in [[Sapporo]], broadcast in [[Hokkaid\u014d]] \n*[[Aomori Broadcasting Corporation|RAB Aomori Broadcasting]], Analog Channel 1, Digital Channel 28 [ID: 1] - Headquartered in [[Aomori, Aomori|Aomori]], broadcast in [[Aomori Prefecture]]\n*[[Television Iwate]], Analog Channel 35, Digital Channel 18 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Morioka, Iwate|Morioka]], broadcast in [[Iwate Prefecture]]\n*Miyagi Television Broadcasting, Analog Channel 34, Digital Channel 24 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Sendai]], broadcast in [[Miyagi Prefecture]]\n*[[Akita Broadcasting System]], Analog Channel 11, Digital Channel 17 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Akita, Akita|Akita]], broadcast in [[Akita Prefecture]]\n*[[Yamagata Broadcasting Company]], Analog Channel 10, Digital Channel 16 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Yamagata, Yamagata|Yamagata]], broadcast in [[Yamagata Prefecture]]\n*[[Fukushima Central Television]], Analog Channel 33, Digital Channel 27 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Fukushima, Fukushima|Fukushima]], broadcast in [[Fukushima Prefecture]]\n*[[Television Niigata Network]], Analog Channel 29, Digital Channel 26 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]], broadcast in [[Niigata Prefecture]]\n*[[Kitanihon Broadcasting]], Analog Channel 1, Digital Channel 28 [ID: 1] - Headquartered in [[Toyama, Toyama|Toyama]], broadcast in [[Toyama Prefecture]]\n*[[TVkanazawa]], Analog Channel 33, Digital Channel 17 [ID:4] - Headquartered in [[Kanazawa, Ishikawa|Kanazawa]], broadcast in [[Ishikawa Prefecture]]\n*[[TV. Shinshu]], Analog Channel 30, Digital Channel 14 [ID: 4] - Headquartered in [[Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]], broadcast in [[Nagano Prefecture]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Nippon TV logo.svg|thumb|left|Logo of Nippon Television until 2014]] -->\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Offices==\n*The headquarters ([[Nittele Tower|Shiodome NTV Tower]]): 6-1, Higashi-Shimbashi Itchome, [[Minato, Tokyo]], Japan\n*Kojimachi Studio (the studios): Nibancho, [[Chiyoda, Tokyo]] (closed in 2019 for further redevelopments)\n*Kansai Branch Office: Kintetsu Dojima Building, 2-2, Dojima Nichome, [[Kita-ku, Osaka]], [[Osaka Prefecture]]\n\n==TV programs==\n{{see also|Category:Nippon Television shows}}\n\n===News===\n*''Zip!'' (morning news directed by Ami K (5:20-8:00 [JST]))\n*''News Every'' (evening news (16:53-19:00 [JST]))\n*''News Zero'' (late-night news (22:54-23:57 [JST]))\n*''NNN News 24'' (24-hour news channel)\n\n===Former Japanese Dramas===\n*''[[Nobuta wo Produce]]'' (\u91ce\u30d6\u30bf\u3002\u3092\u30d7\u30ed\u30c7\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9, 2005)\n*''[[Gokusen]]'' (\u3054\u304f\u305b\u3093, 2002/2005/2008)\n*''[[14-year-old Mother]]'' (14\u624d\u306e\u6bcd, 2006)\n*''[[Yasuko to Kenji]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Mother (Japanese TV series)|Mother]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Kaseifu no Mita]]'' (2011) - the highest watched show of 2011 in Japan \n*''[[Muse no Kagami]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Omae wa Mada Gunma o Shiranai]]'' (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-07/you-dont-know-gunma-yet-manga-gets-live-action-series-film/.111931|title='You don't know GUNMA yet.' Manga Gets Live-Action Series, Film|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=7 February 2017|language=Japanese|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Variety===\n*''Question for one hundred million people!? Waratte Koraete!'' (1\u5104\u4eba\u306e\u5927\u8cea\u554f!?\u7b11\u3063\u3066\u30b3\u30e9\u3048\u3066!)\n*''Guruguru Ninety Nine'' (Gurunai, \u3050\u308b\u3050\u308b\u30ca\u30a4\u30f3\u30c6\u30a3\u30ca\u30a4\u30f3, \u3050\u308b\u30ca\u30a4)\n*''Sekaiichi Uketai Jugyo'' (\u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u53d7\u3051\u305f\u3044\u6388\u696d)\n*''Enta no Kamisama ~the god of Entertainment~'' (\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u306e\u795e\u69d8 ~the god of Entertainment~)\n*''Sekai Marumie! TV Tokusoubu'' (\u4e16\u754c\u307e\u308b\u898b\u3048!\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u7279\u635c\u90e8)\n*''The! Tetsuwan! DASH!!'' (\u30b6!\u9244\u8155!DASH!!)\n*''Gyoretsu no dekiru Horitsu Sodanjo'' (\u884c\u5217\u306e\u51fa\u6765\u308b\u6cd5\u5f8b\u76f8\u8ac7\u6240)\n*''[[Sh\u014dten]]'' (\u7b11\u70b9;the second longest running TV show in Japan, continuously broadcast since May 1966).\n*''[[Gaki no tsukai]]'' ([[Downtown (owarai)|DownTown]]'s ''Gaki no Tsukai ya Arahende!!'', \u30ac\u30ad\u306e\u4f7f\u3044\u3084\u3042\u3089\u3078\u3093\u3067!!)\n*''Arashi no Shukudai-kun'' (\u5d50\u306e\u5bbf\u984c\u304f\u3093)\n*''[[Cartoon KAT-TUN]]'' (\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8\u30a5\u30f3KAT-TUN, K\u0101t\u016bn Kat\u016bn?)\n*''[[AKBingo!]]''\n*''Kyosen to Maetake no Geba Geba 90 pun'' (Gyosen x Maetake's Geba Geba 90 minutes \u5de8\u6cc9\u00d7\u524d\u6b66\u30b2\u30d0\u30b2\u30d090\u5206\uff01)\n*''Karikyura Mashin'' (Curriculumachine \u30ab\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30e9\u30de\u30b7\u30fc\u30f3)\n*''[[Music Lovers]]''\n*''[[God of Music (variety show)|God of Music]]'' (\u97f3\u697d\u306e\u795e\u69d8\uff09\n\n====Former====\n*''Family Wisdom of the Itos'' (\u4f0a\u6771\u5bb6\u306e\u98df\u5353)\n*''Nazo o toke! Masaka no Mistery'' (\u8b0e\u3092\u89e3\u3051!\u307e\u3055\u304b\u306e\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30ea\u30fc)\n*''Magical Zunou Power!!'' (\u30de\u30b8\u30ab\u30eb\u982d\u8133\u30d1\u30ef\u30fc!!) (1990's)\n*''Tokujo! Tensei Shingo'' (\u7279\u4e0a!\u5929\u58f0\u614e\u543e)\n*''[[Dotch Cooking Show]]'' (\u3069\u3063\u3061\u306e\u6599\u7406\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc, Yomiuri Telecastiong Corp.)\n\n===Sport===\n*[[Nippon Professional Baseball|Dramatic Game 1844]] ([[Yomiuri Giants]], baseball games)\n*[[Professional wrestling in Japan|Japanese Professional Wrestling]]\n**[[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] (\u5168\u65e5\u672c\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9, 1972\u20132000 - now under [[JAITS]])\n**[[Pro Wrestling Noah]] (\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30ce\u30a2, 2001\u20132009 - terrestrial, 2009-present - '''Nittele G+''')\n**[[Wrestle-1]] (\"Wrestle-1 Fighting Entertainment\", 2014 - OUTBREAK, live special)\n**[[Fortune KK]] (2014 - premiere show, live special) \n**''[[World Wonder Ring Stardom]]'' (2020-present)\n*[[Hakone Ekiden]]\n*[[Japanese Super Cup|Xerox Super Cup]]\n*[[All Japan High School Soccer Tournament]]\n*[[National Football League]] (NFL)\n*[[Grand Prix motorcycle racing|MotoGP]] \n*[[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series]] (Nittele G+ only)\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]\n*[[CONMEBOL Libertadores]] (Nittele G+ only)\n*[[Yokohama International Women's Marathon]]\n*[[Women's World Cup of Golf]]\n*[[World Ladies Championship Salonpas Cup]]\n*[[Japan LPGA Tour Championship]]\n*[[2013\u201314 Ashes series]]\n\n===Animation===\n{{Main|List of anime aired on Nippon Television}}\nThe company has intimate connections with [[Studio Ghibli]], led by [[Hayao Miyazaki]], and holds the exclusive rights to broadcast their motion pictures. It has also produced and broadcast popular [[anime]] series like ''[[My Hero Academia]]'', ''[[Claymore (manga)|Claymore]]'', ''[[Death Note]]'', ''[[Hajime no Ippo]]'', as well as ''[[Detective Conan]]'' and ''[[Inuyasha]]'' (which are produced through its [[Osaka]] affiliate, [[Yomiuri Telecasting Corporation|Yomiuri TV]]). NTV produced the first, unsuccessful ''[[Doraemon]]'' anime in 1973; when the second, more successful ''Doraemon'' series premiered in 1979, it was on [[TV Asahi]], which remains the franchise's broadcaster to this day. As of now, NTV is currently producing a second anime adaptation of ''[[Hunter \u00d7 Hunter]]''. NTV has also been broadcasting the yearly ''[[Lupin III]]'' TV specials since 1989, which they co-produce with [[TMS Entertainment]]. Nippon Television announced on February 8, 2011, that it would make the anime studio [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]] its subsidiary after becoming the primary stockholder at about 85%, via a third-party allocation of shares for about 1 billion yen (about US$12 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-02-08/ntv-to-make-madhouse-anime-studio-its-subsidiary|title=NTV to Make Madhouse Anime Studio Its Subsidiary|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=8 February 2011|language=Japanese|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.co.jp/english/pressrelease/20110208.html|title=Notification of NTV's Subscription of MADHOUSE Share Allotment|publisher=Nippon Television|date=8 February 2011|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2014, Nippon Television announced that it will purchase a 54.3% stake in [[Tatsunoko Production]] and adopt the studio as a subsidiary.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-01-29/nikkei/ntv-aims-to-buy-anime-studio-tatsunoko-production|title=NTV Buys 54.3% Stake in Anime Studio Tatsunoko Production|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Viewpoints/Culture/Tomy-to-sell-Tatsunoko-Production-to-TV-station|title=Tomy to sell Tatsunoko Production to TV station|publisher=[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun|Nikkei]]|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Special TV programs===\n*Kin-chan and [[Shingo Katori]]'s [[Kasou Taishou|All Japan Costume Grand Prix]] (\u6b3d\u3061\u3083\u3093&\u9999\u53d6\u614e\u543e\u306e\u5168\u65e5\u672c\u4eee\u88c5\u5927\u8cde)\n*24 Hour Television, Love Saves the Earth (24\u6642\u9593\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u300c\u611b\u306f\u5730\u7403\u3092\u6551\u3046\u300d, annual [[telethon]] on the TV stations of NNS)\n*Trans America Ultra Quiz (\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u6a2a\u65ad\u30a6\u30eb\u30c8\u30e9\u30af\u30a4\u30ba)\n**All Japan High School Quiz Championship (\u5168\u56fd\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b66\u6821\u30af\u30a4\u30ba\u9078\u624b\u6a29)\n*[[Nippon Television Music Festival]] (\u65e5\u672c\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u97f3\u697d\u796d)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Television station]]\n*[[Television in Japan]]\n*[[Media of Japan|Japanese media]]\n*[[Hato no ky\u016bjitsu]] (Dove's Day Off), NTV's [[station identification]]\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.ntv.co.jp}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.ntv.co.jp/english}} {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://www.ntv.co.jp/G/ Nittele G+ Official Site] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.ntv.co.jp/zero/ News Zero]\n*[http://www.ntv.co.jp/every/ News Every]\n*[http://www.news24.jp/ Nittele News 24]\n*{{YouTube|user=nittele}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3sKyiJOPmg0 Collection of Nippon Television's Idents, Hato no Kyojitsu]\n\n{{Nippon Television Networks}}\n{{TV-Kanto}}\n{{Japan television networks}}\n\n{{coord|35|39|51.9|N|139|45|35.8|E|region:JP-13_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Nippon Television| ]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Anime companies]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Japanese television networks]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Media companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Nippon News Network]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:Television in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Japan]]\n", "name_user"